Disease of metabolism is a medical condition characterized by abnormalities in the metabolic processes that build or degrade molecules. These conditions can be genetic or acquired and may affect various organ systems in the body, leading to symptoms such as weight loss, fatigue, and weakness. Examples of diseases of metabolism include glycogen storage disease, phenylketonuria, and carbohydrate-deficient glycoprotein syndrome.

Shrimp allergy is a type of crustacean allergy, which means it's an allergy to shrimp and other crustaceans such as crayfish, lobster, and prawns. This type of allergy can cause symptoms like hives, swelling, difficulty breathing, or even a life-threatening reaction known as anaphylaxis. It's important for individuals with a shrimp allergy to avoid consuming any products that contain shrimp and to be cautious when dining out, as many dishes may include hidden sources of shrimp.

Aspirin allergy is a type of drug allergy, which means it's an adverse reaction to aspirin or other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). This can manifest itself through symptoms such as skin rash, hives, swelling, difficulty breathing, and even life-threatening reactions like anaphylaxis. If you have a history of aspirin allergy, it's important to avoid these medications altogether and opt for alternative pain relief options.

Benzylpenicillin allergy is a type of beta lactam allergy.
Benzylpenicillin allergy is a condition where the body's immune system reacts negatively to benzylpenicillin, which is a type of antibiotic. This can cause allergic reactions, such as hives or difficulty breathing. It is important for individuals with this type of allergy to avoid exposure to benzylpenicillin and seek alternative treatment options.

Amoxicillin allergy is a type of beta lactam allergy. Beta-lactam antibiotics, like amoxicillin, are derived from the penicillin mold and have a structure with a beta-lactam ring. This molecular structure makes them susceptible to degradation by certain enzymes produced by bacteria called beta-lactamases. As a result, bacteria that produce these enzymes can resist the effects of beta-lactam antibiotics.
Amoxicillin allergy occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly identifies amoxicillin as an invader and initiates an allergic response. This can result in symptoms such as skin rash, itching, swelling, difficulty breathing, tightness in the chest, wheezing, or even life-threatening anaphylaxis. If you suspect that you may have an amoxicillin allergy, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and treatment.

Ceftriaxone allergy is a type of allergic reaction to the antibiotic ceftriaxone. This can include symptoms such as rash, itching, swelling, difficulty breathing, and even anaphylaxis in severe cases. It is important for individuals who are allergic to ceftriaxone to avoid taking this medication and seek alternative treatment options. If you think you may have a ceftriaxone allergy, it is best to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and management of the allergy.

Carbamazepine is a medication that is commonly used to treat various conditions, including seizures, bipolar disorder, and pain. However, it is not uncommon for individuals to experience allergic reactions to this medication. An allergy to carbamazepine can cause symptoms such as rash, itching, swelling, difficulty breathing, and even life-threatening reactions in rare cases. If you suspect that you have an allergy to carbamazepine, it is important to speak with your healthcare provider immediately, as they can provide appropriate guidance on how to manage your symptoms and avoid future exposure to the medication.

Abacavir allergy is a type of drug allergy, characterized by an allergic reaction to the drug abacavir. Abacavir is an antiviral medication commonly used for treating HIV/AIDS, and it's important to note that this specific drug can cause severe reactions in some patients who are hypersensitive to it. Symptoms of an allergic reaction may include fever, rash, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and shortness of breath. It's crucial for individuals with a known history of abacavir allergy to inform their healthcare provider before starting any new medications or undergoing any medical procedures that may involve the use of this drug.

Isoniazid (INH) is an antibiotic used to treat tuberculosis. It is a sulfur-containing nucleoside analogue that works by inhibiting the enzyme adenosine synthetase, thereby decreasing the production of ATP and leading to bacterial cell death.

Lidocaine allergy is a type of drug allergy, which means that the body has an allergic reaction to lidocaine. Lidocaine is a local anesthetic used in medical procedures such as injections and surgeries. It is also available over-the-counter in the form of creams and ointments for pain relief. When someone with a lidocaine allergy comes into contact with the drug, their immune system reacts, causing symptoms such as itching, swelling, hives, difficulty breathing, and even anaphylaxis, a life-threatening allergic reaction. If you have a history of lidocaine allergy, it is important to inform your healthcare provider before any medical procedure that may involve the use of lidocaine.

Mepivacaine allergy is a type of drug allergy that specifically has an allergic reaction to mepivacaine. It can be defined as a condition where someone experiences an adverse reaction when exposed to mepivacaine, which is a local anesthetic used for pain relief during medical procedures.
It's important to note that not everyone who is allergic to mepivacaine will have the same symptoms or severity of reactions. Some common symptoms may include itching, swelling, redness, and difficulty breathing. In more severe cases, anaphylaxis, a life-threatening allergic reaction, can occur.
It's also worth mentioning that mepivacaine allergy is sometimes referred to as carbocaine or polocaine allergy due to the similar structure of these local anesthetics and their related compounds. However, it's important to note that not all individuals with a mepivacaine allergy will also be allergic to these other agents.
In conclusion, mepivacaine allergy is a type of drug allergy that involves an adverse reaction to mepivacaine and can range from mild to severe symptoms, including life-threatening anaphylaxis.

Phenytoin allergy is a type of drug allergy that occurs when someone has an allergic reaction to phenytoin, which is also known as Dilantin. Phenytoin is a medication that is often used to treat seizure disorders. When a person develops a phenytoin allergy, it means that their immune system has identified the drug as harmful and is attempting to combat it by producing antibodies against it. This can result in symptoms such as skin rash, itching, swelling, difficulty breathing, and even anaphylaxis, which is a life-threatening allergic reaction. If you have a phenytoin allergy, it is important to avoid taking the medication and work with your healthcare provider to find alternative treatments for your seizure disorder.

Tubocurarine allergy is a type of drug allergy that involves an allergic reaction to tubocurarine. It is also known as DTC allergy, which stands for "drug-induced thrombocytopenia and bleeding." Hexamethylene diisocyanate (HDI) is a type of isocyanate that can cause allergic reactions in some individuals. This condition, known as hexamethylene diisocyanate-induced asthma, is characterized by difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness. It is believed to be triggered by exposure to the fumes of HDI, which can release small particles that irritate the airways. In some cases, it may also be caused by a reaction to other isocyanates or to other substances present in the workplace environment. Treatment options for hexamethylene diisocyanate-induced asthma typically involve avoiding exposure to HDI and using medications such as bronchodilators, corticosteroids, and leukotriene modifiers to manage symptoms. It is important to note that this condition can be serious and life-threatening in some cases. If you suspect that you may have hexamethylene diisocyanate-induced asthma or are exposed to HDI regularly, it is essential to consult with an allergist or other medical professional for proper evaluation and treatment.

Isocyanates are a type of allergen that can trigger allergic asthma symptoms in some individuals. Isocyanates are commonly found in spray foam insulation products and other construction materials, as well as in the production of certain plastics and resins. If you have isocyanate-induced allergic asthma, it means that your airways become inflamed and constricted when you come into contact with these substances. Symptoms can include coughing, wheezing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath, and they can range from mild to severe in intensity. It is important for people with isocyanate-induced allergic asthma to avoid exposure to these substances as much as possible and to have a written allergy plan that outlines the necessary precautions and procedures in case of exposure. If you suspect that you may have isocyanate-induced allergic asthma, it is important to consult with an allergist or other healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Allergic asthma to MDI, also known as 4,4-diisocyanate diphenylmethane allergic asthma or simply isocyanates allergic asthma, is a type of asthma that is triggered by exposure to certain chemicals, such as 4,4-diisocyanate diphenylmethane. It is characterized by respiratory symptoms, including wheezing, coughing, and shortness of breath, which are worsened by exposure to the allergen. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and bronchial provocation testing. Treatment may include avoidance of allergens, medications to reduce inflammation and improve airway function, and peak flow monitoring to track symptoms and adjust treatment as needed.

Toluene 1,2-diisocyanate (TDI) is a type of isocyanates that can trigger allergic asthma in some individuals. Methyl isocyanate allergic asthma, also known as MIC-induced asthma, refers to a type of asthma triggered by exposure to methyl isocyanate (MIC), a colorless gas with a strong odor. This condition shares similarities with other types of isocyanate-induced asthma, which are characterized by airway hyperresponsiveness and inflammation in response to exposure to various isocyanates.

Individuals with methyl isocyanate allergic asthma may experience symptoms such as wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, coughing, and itchy or watery eyes after coming into contact with MIC. In some cases, exposure to even low levels of the gas can trigger these symptoms, making it important for those who work with or around MIC to take precautions to avoid unnecessary exposure.

Diagnosis of methyl isocyanate allergic asthma typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and laboratory testing, such as skin prick tests or inhalation challenges. Treatment for this condition may include bronchodilators to relieve airway constriction, corticosteroids to reduce inflammation, and leukotriene modifiers to prevent further asthma exacerbations.

It is important to note that not everyone who comes into contact with MIC will develop methyl isocyanate allergic asthma, but some individuals may be more susceptible due to genetic or other factors. Therefore, it is crucial for those working with or around this gas to follow proper safety protocols and seek medical attention if they experience any respiratory symptoms after exposure.

If you suspect that you have benzo d isothiazol 3 one allergic contact dermatitis, it's important to avoid any products containing BIT, consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment, and consider using alternative products formulated without this ingredient.

Phthalyl group allergy is a type of drug allergy, where the allergic trigger is the phthalyl group. It has a specific definition as a drug allergy with an allergic trigger to the phthalyl group. Phthalyl group allergy shares an exact synonym with phthalyl allergy.

Alcuronium bromide allergy is a type of drug allergies. Drug allergies occur when the body's immune system reacts to a medication, causing an adverse reaction. These reactions can range from mild to severe and may include symptoms such as itching or hives, swelling, difficulty breathing, or even life-threatening reactions. It is important for individuals with a history of drug allergies to inform their healthcare provider of any medications they have taken in the past, as well as any allergic reactions they have experienced. In some cases, alternative medications may need to be prescribed to avoid triggering an allergic reaction.

Gallamine allergy is a type of drug allergy that has an allergic trigger, which could be gallamine. The term "gallamine" refers to a specific compound used in some medications. It is important for individuals with this allergy to avoid coming into contact with the substance responsible for their allergy. In order to ensure safety and prevent adverse reactions, it is crucial that those affected by gallamine allergy are aware of which medications contain gallamine and take necessary precautions when using any prescription or over-the-counter drugs.

2 4 dinitrophenyl allergic contact dermatitis is a type of allergic reaction to the 2,4-dinitrophenyl group. This can cause skin irritation and discomfort for those who are sensitive to it. It is important to be aware of this allergy and take necessary precautions when coming into contact with substances that may contain the 2,4-dinitrophenyl group.

chlamydia pneumonia is a type of bacterial pneumonia that has material basis in the bacterium Chlamydia pneumoniae.

Bacterial sepsis is a serious bacterial infection that occurs when harmful bacteria multiply rapidly and spread throughout the body. It can affect multiple organs and tissues, leading to severe complications such as organ failure, seizures, or even death if not treated promptly and effectively.
The causes of bacterial sepsis include:
1. Infections from surgery, such as a wound infection or an infection after a medical procedure.
2. Infections from other sources, such as urinary tract infections (UTIs), skin infections, pneumonia, and gastrointestinal infections.
3. Bacterial infections that are spread through close contact with another person, such as strep throat or tuberculosis.
4. Bloodstream infections caused by bacteria that enter the bloodstream from other parts of the body.
Bacterial sepsis can be difficult to diagnose and treat due to its wide range of symptoms, which may include fever, chills, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, confusion, nausea or vomiting, severe diarrhea, abdominal pain, and yellowing of the skin or eyes (jaundice). Early detection and treatment are essential to prevent complications and improve outcomes.
Treatment for bacterial sepsis typically involves administering antibiotics to target and kill the harmful bacteria causing the infection. In severe cases, hospitalization may be required, along with other supportive treatments such as intravenous (IV) fluids, oxygen therapy, and nutritional support. Preventative measures include practicing good hygiene habits, receiving recommended vaccinations, and seeking medical attention promptly for any signs of infection or illness.

Polymavirus associated nephropathy, also known as PVAN, is a type of viral infectious disease that has material basis in the BK polyomavirus and primarily affects the kidneys. It is characterized by renal syndrome, which includes symptoms such as fever, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, decreased urine output, and sometimes hemorrhagic cystitis. PVAN can be transmitted through contact with contaminated food or water, as well as through respiratory droplets from infected individuals. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have been exposed to PVAN or are experiencing symptoms of the disease. Early diagnosis and treatment can improve outcomes for those affected by this condition.

Autoimmune peripheral neuropathy is a condition in which the immune system mistakenly attacks and damages the peripheral nerves, causing inflammation, pain, numbness, and weakness in the extremities. It is an autoimmune disease that affects the peripheral nervous system, leading to peripheral neuropathy. The exact cause of autoimmune peripheral neuropathy is not yet fully understood, but it can be triggered by certain environmental factors and genetic predisposition. Treatment typically involves a combination of medications, physical therapy, and lifestyle changes to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Autoimmune uveitis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the eyes, ears, nose, and throat. It is characterized by inflammation in the uveal tract, which can cause pain, redness, and blurred vision. Autoimmune uveitis is a serious condition that requires medical treatment to prevent long-term damage to the eyes.

Autoimmune Optic Neuritis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the peripheral nervous system, specifically in the optic nerve. It occurs when the immune system attacks and damages the optic nerve, leading to vision loss. The condition typically affects people between the ages of 20 and 50, with women being more commonly affected than men. Symptoms may include sudden painless vision loss, blurred or double vision, sensitivity to light, and a decreased ability to see in low-light conditions. Treatment options may include corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and plasma exchange therapy, depending on the severity of the condition and other factors such as the patient's overall health.

Autoimmune gastritis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the stomach. It occurs when the immune system mistakenly attacks healthy cells in the stomach lining, causing inflammation and damage. Symptoms may include abdominal pain or discomfort, bloating, nausea, vomiting, and a feeling of fullness after eating. Treatment typically involves medications to suppress the immune system and reduce inflammation, as well as changes in diet to avoid irritants that can cause further damage to the stomach lining. It is important for individuals with autoimmune gastritis to work with a healthcare professional to develop an appropriate treatment plan.

Autoimmune pancreatitis is a condition where the immune system attacks the pancreas, leading to inflammation and damage. It can cause pain, swelling, and difficulty digesting food. It's considered an autoimmune disease of the endocrine system because it affects the glands that produce hormones that control blood sugar levels. Treatment often involves corticosteroids to reduce inflammation, but other medications may be needed as well. In severe cases, surgery may be required to remove the affected pancreas tissue.

Juvenile ankylosing spondylitis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the musculoskeletal system, with onset typically occurring during childhood or adolescence. It is characterized by inflammation in the sacroiliac joints and the spine, which can lead to pain, stiffness, and limited mobility over time. The exact cause of juvenile ankylosing spondylitis is not fully understood, but it is believed to be triggered by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. There is no cure for the condition, but treatment options such as medication and physical therapy can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Drug-induced lupus erythematosus (DIL) is a type of lupus erythematosus that occurs due to the use of certain drugs. It is characterized by symptoms similar to those of systemic lupus erythematosus, but it is triggered by medications rather than an autoimmune disease. DIL can cause skin rashes, joint pain, and inflammation in the kidneys and other organs. Treatment typically involves stopping the offending drug and using corticosteroids to reduce inflammation. It is important to note that not all drugs can cause lupus erythematosus, and only a small number of drugs are known to trigger this condition. If you suspect that you may have DIL, it is important to speak with your healthcare provider to receive an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.

Autoimmune glomerulonephritis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the urogenital tract and specifically involves inflammation in the renal glomeruli. It is characterized by the production of antibodies that attack the body's own tissues, leading to damage in these areas. The condition can cause symptoms such as proteinuria (excessive protein in the urine), hematuria (bloody urine), and swelling in the legs and feet due to fluid accumulation. Autoimmune glomerulonephritis is typically diagnosed through a combination of physical exams, blood tests, and imaging studies such as ultrasound or CT scans. Treatment options may include medications to suppress the immune system, anti-inflammatory drugs, and dietary changes to manage symptoms and slow down the progression of the disease.

Autoimmune cardiomyopathy is a condition where the immune system mistakenly attacks and damages the heart muscle. This can lead to a weakening of the heart, making it more difficult for the heart to pump blood efficiently. It is an autoimmune disease that primarily affects the heart, causing deterioration in its function over time.
Autoimmune atherosclerosis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the cardiovascular system, specifically involving the buildup of plaque in the arteries.

Autoimmune vasculitis is a type of autoimmune disease characterized by inflammation of the blood vessels. It can affect various parts of the circulatory system, including arteries, veins, and capillaries. There are several subtypes of autoimmune vasculitis, each with its own set of symptoms and locations affected. Common symptoms include skin rashes, joint pain, fatigue, and fever. Treatment typically involves medications to suppress the immune system and reduce inflammation.

Pemphigus gestationis is a type of pemphigus that affects the skin during pregnancy. It is caused by an autoimmune response, where the body's own immune system attacks healthy cells in the skin. The condition is characterized by blistered skin, and it can cause significant discomfort and pain for those affected. There is no cure for pemphigus gestationis, but treatment options are available to help manage the symptoms and prevent further damage to the skin.

Livedoid vasculitis is a type of vasculitis that affects small blood vessels, causing them to become inflamed. It typically presents with purple or red skin ulcers and can be associated with conditions such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis. The exact cause is not fully understood, but it is believed to involve a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Treatment options for livedoid vasculitis may include corticosteroids, immunosuppressive medications, and other disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs). It's important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

The Hirata disease, also known as the insulin autoimmune syndrome, is an autoimmune disorder that affects the endocrine system. It is characterized by hypoglycemia, which occurs when antibodies attack and damage the insulin-producing cells in the pancreas. This leads to a reduced production of insulin, causing blood sugar levels to drop abnormally low. The disease can also cause other symptoms such as weight loss, fatigue, and anorexia. It is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition, as prompt treatment can help manage the symptoms and prevent long-term complications.

Neoprene Allergy is a term used to describe an allergic reaction to neoprene, which is a type of synthetic rubber commonly found in products such as wetsuits and shoes. Symptoms can include skin rash, itching, and swelling, and the allergy can be triggered by contact with neoprene products. It's important to avoid exposure to neoprene if you have a neoprene allergy to prevent further irritation or allergic reactions.
Neoprene allergy is an exact synonym for N,N-diethylthiourea allergic contact dermatitis.

Cefotiam allergy is a type of cephalosporin allergy, which refers to an allergic reaction triggered by the antibiotic Cefotiam. This type of allergy specifically targets individuals who are sensitive to this particular antibiotic, resulting in an adverse response when it is administered.

Seminal vesicle acute gonorrhea, also known as seminal vesiculitis caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae infection. Symptoms include back pain, perineal pain, pain during ejaculation, and hematospermia (bloody sperm in the semen). Chikungunya is a viral infectious disease that results from infection with the Chikungunya virus, which is transmitted through a bite from an Aedes mosquito. The symptoms of the disease include fever, arthralgia (pain in the joints), and maculopapular rash.

Human Granulocytic Anaplasmosis (HGA) is a type of ehrlichiosis that affects humans and is caused by the bacterium Anaplasma phagocytophilum. It is transmitted through the bite of infected Amblyomma americanum ticks. Symptoms include headache, fever, muscle aches, fatigue, and a rash.

Ehrlichiosis is a type of infectious disease caused by the bacterium Ehrlichia ewingae. It can affect both humans and animals, with different species of ticks serving as the primary vectors for transmitting the disease. The symptoms of ehrlichiosis vary depending on the specific species of Ehrlichia and the host being infected, but common symptoms include fever, chills, headache, muscle aches, joint pain, and a rash. In some cases, ehrlichiosis can be fatal if left untreated.

Mineral metabolism diseases are a group of disorders that affect the way the body processes minerals. They can be caused by genetic factors, environmental exposure to certain substances, or other causes such as hormone imbalances or infections. Some common examples of mineral metabolism diseases include hyperparathyroidism, hypocalcemia, and osteoporosis. Treatment for these conditions often involves addressing the underlying cause and managing symptoms through medication and lifestyle changes.

African tick bite fever is a type of spotted fever that has material basis in Rickettsia africae, which is transmitted by ticks (Amblyomma hebraeum and Amblyomma variegatum). The infection has symptoms such as fever, eschar, and maculopapular rash.

Astrakhan spotted fever is a type of illness that has been identified as having a material basis in the bacteria Rickettsia conorii subsp caspia. It is believed to be transmitted by ticks, specifically the species Rhipicephalus pumilio and Rhipicephalus sanguineus. The symptoms of Astrakhan spotted fever include fever, maculopapular rash on extremities, eschar (usually single), regional adenopathy, and is characterized by a spotted rash that can appear as macules or papules. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have been exposed to this type of illness.

Indian tick typhus is a type of spotted fever that has material basis in the bacterium Rickettsia conorii subsp indica, which is transmitted by the brown dog tick (Rhipicephalus sanguineus). The infection causes symptoms such as fever, eschar, regional lymphadenopathy, and maculopapular rash on extremities.

Israeli tick typhus, also known as Israeli spotted fever, is a type of bacterial infection that is spread through the bites of infected ticks. It is caused by the Rickettsia conorii subspecies israelensis, which is specific to this disease. The symptoms include fever, maculopapular rash on extremities, eschar, and regional adenopathy.

Far Eastern Spotted Fever (FESF) is a type of spotted fever caused by the bacterium Rickettsia heilongjiangensis, which is transmitted through the bites of ticks belonging to the species Haemaphysalis concinna. The infection typically presents with symptoms such as fever, maculopapular rash, eschar, and regional lymphadenopathy. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have been bitten by a tick or if you develop any of these symptoms. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent serious complications.

Flinders Island spotted fever is a type of spotted fever that has a material basis in Rickettsia honei and is transmitted by ticks, specifically Amblyomma cajennense. The infection causes mild spotted fever symptoms such as eschar and lymphadenopathy. Another name for this illness is Thai tick typhus, and it's also related to FISF.

Japanese spotted fever is indeed a type of spotted fever caused by the bacterium Rickettsia japonica, which can be transmitted through ticks such as Dermacentor taiwanensis and Haemaphysalis flava. The symptoms include fever, eschars (dead skin surrounded by a halo of liv

Rickettsia parkeri spotted fever is a type of spotted fever caused by the bacterium Rickettsia parkeri. It is transmitted to humans through the bites of ticks, specifically those of the species Amblyomma maculatum. The infection causes symptoms such as fever, headache, rash, and eschar (a moist, dead skin fragment).

Rocky Mountain spotted fever (RMSF) is a type of spotted fever that has material basis in the bacterium Rickettsia rickettsii, which is transmitted by ticks (Dermacentor variabilis and Dermacentor andersoni). The infection typically causes fever, headache, abdominal pain, and a maculopapular or papular rash that progresses into petechial or purpuric lesions. RMSF is a serious illness that can lead to death if not treated promptly and properly. Symptoms may appear within 3-14 days after the tick bite, but some cases have a longer incubation period of up to two weeks. Prevention measures include wearing protective clothing, using insect repellent, checking for ticks after outdoor activities, and removing any attached ticks promptly with tweezers. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent long-term complications or death.

Oropharyngeal anthrax is a severe form of gastrointestinal anthrax caused by the bacterium Bacillus anthracis. It usually results from the ingestion of contaminated meat or other animal products, and symptoms can include vomiting blood, diarrhea, loss of appetite, and severe abdominal pain. The infection can spread to the mucosa of the throat and has a high mortality rate if left untreated. Proper medical care is crucial in treating oropharyngeal anthrax to improve chances of survival.

Erysipeloid is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection located in the skin, has a material basis in Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae, which is transmitted by contact with infected animals. The infection causes symptoms such as redness, tenderness, and warmth of the skin.

Adiaspiromycosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis that affects the lungs and skin, and is caused by the fungi Chrysosporium parvum or Emmonsia crescens. It results in a disseminated granulomatous pulmonary process and cutaneous infection in rodents, small wild mammals, and humans.

Invasive aspergillosis is a serious fungal infection of the lung, often seen in patients with acute leukemia or those who have received tissue transplants. It is caused by the Aspergillus fungus and can spread to other parts of the body through the bloodstream. Symptoms may include pulmonary nodules and hemorrhage. The disease has a strong clinical presentation, with symptoms like pulmonary nodules and hemorrhage being common.

tinea barbae is a type of skin disease that results in a fungal infection, affecting the horny layer of the epidermis in the bearded areas on the face and neck. It has a material basis in either Trichophyton mentagrophytes or Trichophyton verrucosum, and can also affect hair, nails, and cause inflammatory kerion-like plaques. The condition is sometimes referred to as dermatophytosis of the beard.

Ectothrix Infectious Disease, also known as tinea capitis, is a type of hair disease caused by fungal infections in the cuticle of the hair. It has a material basis in various species of dermatophytes such as Microsporum canis and Trichophyton equinum. The disease typically affects the scalp and is characterized by symptoms like itching, redness, and flaking of the skin.

endothrix infectious disease is a type of tinea capitis, which is a fungal infection of the hair. This disease has a material basis in Ascomycota fungi, particularly those that belong to the dermatophytes group. These fungi produce arthroconidia within the hair shaft, specifically located on the cuticle of the hair. The definition of endothrix infectious disease is a tinea capitis that results in a fungal infection located in the hair and has a material basis in Ascomycota fungi that belong to a group called dermatophytes.

tinea imbricata is a type of tinea corporis that results in a fungal infection in the skin, and has a material basis in Trichophyton concentricum. It is characterized by ring-like growths in overlapping circles that may have an autosomal dominant genetic predisposition.

Disease by infectious agent is a medical condition that occurs as the result of infection with one or more pathogenic microbial agents, such as viruses, bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. These microorganisms can cause a wide range of illnesses, from mild to severe and even life-threatening. Disease by infectious agent is also known as infectious disease, which refers specifically to any medical condition caused by the invasion of an organism's body by pathogenic microorganisms, such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, or parasites.

la crosse encephalitis is a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the brain. It has a material basis in the La Crosse virus, which is transmitted by the treehole mosquito Ochlerotatus triseriatus. The infection has symptoms such as seizures, headache, fever, coma, and paralysis.
Exact synonyms for la crosse encephalitis include California Encephalitis and Neuroinvasive California encephalitis virus infection.

Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH) is a rare, life-threatening condition that occurs when the body's immune system becomes overactive and attacks its own cells and tissues. It primarily affects the liver, spleen, lymph nodes, bone marrow, and blood cells.

Symptoms of HLH may include fever, weight loss, fatigue, abdominal pain, enlarged liver and spleen, pancytopenia (low levels of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets), and swollen lymph nodes. In some cases, there is also jaundice due to liver damage.

HLH can be caused by a variety of underlying conditions, such as infections, cancer, or genetic disorders. It is often difficult to diagnose, as its symptoms are similar to those of many other conditions. Diagnosis may involve blood tests, imaging studies, and bone marrow biopsy.

Treatment for HLH usually involves addressing the underlying cause and providing supportive care, such as intravenous immunoglobulin and corticosteroids. In some cases, a stem cell transplant may be necessary. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to improve outcomes in this life-threatening condition.

Dengue Shock Syndrome (DSS) is a severe form of dengue disease characterized by circulatory collapse, hypotension, narrow pulse pressure (less than or equal to 20mm Hg), or frank shock. It is accompanied by symptoms such as easy bruising, blood spots, bleeding gums, and nosebleeds. DSS has a material basis in the dengue virus, which is transmitted through Aedes mosquito bites. The symptoms usually occur after two to six days of initial symptoms and can lead to circulatory failure and even death if not treated promptly.

sinusitis is a type of paranasal sinus disease, characterized by inflammation in the paranasal sinuses. This condition can be caused by various factors such as bacterial, fungal, viral infections or allergic or autoimmune issues. Symptoms usually include fever, weakness, fatigue, cough and congestion. Additionally, there may be mucus drainage in the back of the throat, called postnasal drip.

Secretory diarrhea is a type of diarrhea characterized by an increase in the active secretion or inhibition of absorption, causing little to no structural damage. The most common cause of this type of diarrhea is a cholera toxin that stimulates the secretion of anions, especially chloride ions.

Osmotic diarrhea is a type of diarrhea that occurs when too much water is drawn into the bowels, resulting from maldigestion or excessive consumption of osmotic laxatives. It can also be caused by an excess intake of certain nutrients such as magnesium and vitamin C, or undigested lactose in individuals without lactose intolerance. Symptoms include diarrhea and constipation.

Motility-related diarrhea, also known as hypermotility bowel or irritable bowel syndrome with diarrhea (IBS-D), is a condition characterized by abnormal intestinal motility. This can result in symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, frequent loose stools, and urgency to defecate. In some cases, it may also be associated with other gastrointestinal symptoms like constipation, nausea, and vomiting. The exact cause of motility-related diarrhea is not fully understood, but it can be triggered by various factors such as stress, certain medications, infections, or a condition called small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO). Treatment options for motility-related diarrhea may include dietary changes, medications to regulate the gut, and psychological therapies. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional if you are experiencing persistent or severe symptoms of motility-related diarrhea.

Inflammatory diarrhea is a type of diarrhea that occurs when there is damage to the mucosal lining or brush border, which leads to a passive loss of protein-rich fluids and a decreased ability to absorb these lost fluids. It can be caused by various factors such as bacterial infections, viral infections, parasitic infections, autoimmune problems like inflammatory bowel diseases, tuberculosis, colon cancer, and enteritis.

Superficial mycosis is a type of fungal infection that affects the outermost layer of skin or hair shaft. It does not involve any invasion of living tissue and there is no cellular response from the host. Other synonyms for superficial mycosis include steroid-modified tinea infection and piedra.

Cutaneous mycosis is a type of fungal infectious disease that occurs when certain types of fungi invade and grow in the keratinized layers of skin, hair, or nails. These fungi can cause skin lesions to form, which extend deeper into the epidermis. It is important to note that not all fungal infections are cutaneous mycoses; other types of fungal infections may affect different parts of the body or have different clinical presentations.

subcutaneous mycosis is a fungal infection that occurs when certain types of fungi penetrate the skin or subcutaneous tissue, causing an infection. This can happen during or after a skin trauma, and can affect the dermis or even deeper layers of skin. It is considered to be a type of infectious disease caused by fungus.

Podoconiosis is a type of elephantiasis that affects the lower extremities due to an inflammatory reaction to mineral particles in irritant red clay soils. It is caused by a genetic abnormality and can lead to lymphadema if left untreated.

Acute diarrhea is a type of gastrointestinal disorder that is characterized by the frequent and rapid loss of loose or liquid stools. It typically lasts for a short period, often just a few days, and can range from mild to severe in its severity. Acute diarrhea is commonly caused by a viral or bacterial infection and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as abdominal pain, cramping, nausea, vomiting, fever, and dehydration. It can be dangerous, especially for young children, the elderly, and people with weakened immune systems, as it can lead to complications such as dehydration, electrolyte imbalances, and even death in severe cases. Therefore, it is important to seek medical attention if you or someone you know is experiencing acute diarrhea, especially if it is accompanied by these symptoms or if it lasts for an extended period of time.

Botulism is a type of food poisoning caused by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. It is transmitted through ingestion of food that contains spores of the bacteria. Once ingested, these spores germinate in the intestine and produce toxins that can cause muscle weakness and paralysis. There are several types of botulism, including intestinal botulism, which affects the intestines, and botulism poisoning, which affects the nervous system. Intestinal botulism is a type of botulism that involves intoxication caused by botulinum neurotoxins (BoNTA, B, E and F) in adults, and has a material basis in Clostridium botulinum A, B, E, and F.

Correct, asymptomatic dengue refers to a type of dengue disease where the infected individual does not exhibit any symptoms. It is caused by the Dengue virus, which has four serotypes (Dengue virus 1, 2, 3 and 4) that are transmitted through the bite of an Aedes mosquito. The infection does not produce any noticeable symptoms, making it difficult to diagnose without further tests or monitoring. However, it is still possible for asymptomatic individuals to spread the virus to others, so it's important to take preventive measures such as wearing protective clothing and using mosquito nets in areas where dengue is prevalent.

Kartagener syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the cilia in the respiratory system. It causes chronic sinusitis, bronchiectasis (a condition where the airways become wider and produce excess mucus), and situs inversus with dextrocardia (a heart malformation where the organs are on the opposite side of the body). The disorder is caused by a defect in the cilia, which leads to an imbalance in the movement of fluids and mucus. It is also associated with certain genetic mutations.

Chronic adenoiditis is an upper respiratory tract disease characterized by persistent inflammation, infection or obstruction of the adenoid tissue. It is usually caused by chronic infections with viruses and bacteria, such as the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), which is a member of the Epstein-Barr virus family. Chronic adenoiditis can cause persistent nasal congestion, difficulty swallowing, and other respiratory problems. It is more common in children and often occurs alongside other upper respiratory tract infections, such as tonsillitis or bronchitis. The treatment of chronic adenoiditis may involve antibiotics, corticosteroids, or surgery to remove the affected tissue.

Laryngotracheitis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease that involves inflammation of both the larynx and trachea. This condition is often caused by viral infection, which can lead to the inhalation of foreign substances into the airway, potentially causing obstruction or narrowing of the windpipe.

Pontiac fever is a type of legionellosis, which is a group of bacterial infections that can cause illness. Legionella pneumophila is the causative agent of Pontiac fever and it affects the respiratory system. It is transmitted through droplet spread transmission, meaning that it can be spread by breathing in droplets from an infected person or by coming into contact with contaminated surfaces and objects.
Symptoms of Pontiac fever typically include fever, headache, muscle aches, and sometimes nausea and chills. The illness usually lasts for 2 to 5 days and can be treated with antibiotics. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have been exposed to Legionella bacteria or if you develop symptoms of Pontiac fever.

Aspiration pneumonia is a type of bacterial pneumonia that occurs when an individual inhales small amounts of oropharyngeal secretions, such as saliva or food particles, containing bacteria. This can happen due to dysphagia or difficulty swallowing, which may be caused by conditions like gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), Parkinson's disease, or a stroke. Aspiration pneumonia can present with symptoms such as tachypnea (fast breathing), cough, and fever. It is an acute inflammatory response in the lungs caused by bacterial infection, which requires medical attention and treatment to resolve the symptoms and prevent complications.

Pulmonary aspergilloma is a type of lung disease that occurs when Aspergillus fungus grows in the air sacs (alveoli) of the lungs. It can cause symptoms such as coughing, chest pain, and shortness of breath, and is often diagnosed through imaging tests like CT scans or X-rays. Treatment options depend on the severity of the disease but may involve surgery to remove the fungal mass or antifungal medications to treat the infection. It is important for those with pulmonary aspergilloma to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an effective treatment plan and manage any complications that may arise.
