Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis (IPF) is a type of pulmonary fibrosis characterized by the scarring of the lung. It is also known as Fibrocytic Pulmonary Dysplasia and Familial IPF when there is a strong family history of the disease. The exact cause of IPF is unknown, but it is believed to be related to abnormal interstitial lung scarring and may involve both genetic and environmental factors. It typically affects people over the age of 50 and is more common in men than women. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and fatigue, and the disease usually progresses slowly over time. There is no cure for IPF, but medications can help manage symptoms and slow down the progression of the disease.

Cryptogenic organizing pneumonia (COP) is a type of interstitial lung disease characterized by inflammation and scarring in the lungs. It can cause symptoms such as cough, fever, fatigue, weight loss, and crackling sounds when listened to with a stethoscope. COP has exact synonyms including bronchiolitis obliterans organising pneumonia and idiopathic interstitial pneumonia.

Desquamative interstitial pneumonia (DIP) is a type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia. It has several distinctive features, including the presence of bronchiolocentric alveolar macrophages in alveolar spaces and interstitial inflammation. Additionally, mild bronchiolar fibrosis and chronic inflammation are also observed in DIP.

DIP is sometimes referred to by other terms, such as RBILD (recent onset, benign idiopathic interstitial pneumonia), familial desquamative interstitial pneumonitis, and respiratory bronchiolitis-associated interstitial lung disease.

It is important to note that DIP can be challenging to diagnose as it has many similarities with other types of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia. A thorough evaluation, including a combination of clinical presentation, radiographic findings, and laboratory tests, is necessary for an accurate diagnosis.

Lymphoid interstitial pneumonia is a specific type of idiopathic interstitial pneumonia that presents with symptoms such as a cough. It is characterized by the diffuse infiltration of interstitial tissue mainly involving T lymphocytes, plasma cells and macrophages, and often accompanied by lymphoid hyperplasia. The onset is usually gradual over 3 or more years with symptoms such as progressive cough and breathlessness, occasionally fever, weight loss, chest pain and arthralgia. As the disease progresses, crackles may be detected in the lungs.

Inhalation anthrax is a type of disease caused by the bacteria Bacillus anthracis. The spores of this bacterium are commonly found in soil and can be inhaled into the lungs, leading to infection in the lung tissue and lymph nodes. Symptoms typically begin as mild flu-like symptoms such as fever, cough, chest pain, and shortness of breath. As the disease progresses, symptoms may become more severe, including vomiting blood, seizures, and even death if left untreated. Inhalation anthrax is a serious and potentially fatal condition that requires prompt medical treatment.

lower respiratory tract disease is the same as an illness that affects the lower part of the respiratory system, which includes the bronchi and bronchioles. This can include conditions such as bronchitis and pneumonia, which involve inflammation or infection of the airways. Other possible lower respiratory tract diseases may include obstructive disorders like asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), as well as infections like tuberculosis. Overall, lower respiratory tract diseases can have a variety of causes and present with a range of symptoms, such as coughing, wheezing, shortness of breath, and chest pain.

Tuberculous salpingitis is a type of fallopian tube disease that occurs when the fallopian tubes become infected with Mycobacterium tuberculosis, leading to inflammation and formation of granulomas in the tubes. It is classified as a urogenital tuberculosis because it primarily affects the reproductive organs, particularly the fallopian tubes. The condition can cause a variety of symptoms such as abnormal bleeding, pelvic pain, and fever. In some cases, it may lead to infertility if the infection spreads to other reproductive organs or causes blockages in the tubes. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have tuberculous salpingitis as prompt treatment can help prevent further damage and improve outcomes.

Autoimmune Polyendocrine Syndrome Type 1 (APS1) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple endocrine glands at the same time. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that both copies of the gene need to be inherited for the disease to develop. APS1 can cause problems with the functioning of the immune system, leading to auto-reactivity against endocrine organs. The disorder is also known as Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndrome Type 1 (APS1), Whitaker syndrome, and autoimmune polyendocrinopathy-candidiasis-ectodermal dystrophy.

Autoimmune Polyendocrine Syndrome Type 2 (APS type 2) is a condition that affects the endocrine system, causing it to malfunction due to an abnormal immune response. This leads to the production of autoantibodies against the endocrine organs and glands, resulting in a range of symptoms such as excessive or insufficient hormone production, growth disturbances, and other related issues. APS type 2 is considered more heterogeneous than its counterpart, APS type 1, and has not been linked to one specific gene. It is also known as Schmidt Syndrome.

Cutaneous lupus erythematosus, also known as cutaneous lupus or SLE (systemic lupus erythematosus) with a skin-specific focus, is a type of autoimmune disorder. It occurs when the immune system mistakenly attacks healthy cells and tissues in the body. In this case, the targeted tissue is the skin, leading to the development of skin lesions or rashes that can be triggered by sunlight exposure. The disease can affect individuals across all ages and ethnicities, but it is more common among women than men. Treatment for cutaneous lupus usually involves a combination of medications such as topical corticosteroids, antimalarials, and immunosuppressants to manage symptoms and prevent the progression of the disease.

Kunjin encephalitis is a type of West Nile encephalitis that results from infection located in the brain, has material basis in the Kunjin virus, a subtype of West Nile Virus, and is transmitted by Culex annulirostris mosquito bites. The infection has symptoms such as fever, rigor, headache, confusion, and lethargy.
tick borne encephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease.

Monogenic diseases are those that result from mutations in a single gene, and they often have a clear genetic basis. These diseases can be dominant, semi-dominant, or recessive, depending on the specific alleles involved. It's important to note that while monogenic diseases may have a strong genetic component, other environmental factors can also contribute to their development and progression.

Powassan encephalitis is a type of tick-borne encephalitis caused by the Powassan virus, which is transmitted by Ixodes and Dermacentor species of ticks. Symptoms include headache, fever, vomiting, stiff neck, sleepiness, breathing distress, tremors, confusion, seizures, paralysis, and coma. It has a material basis in the Powassan virus and can have severe consequences if left untreated.

Erythema multiforme is a type of skin disease characterized by the sudden appearance of target-shaped, bright red patches on the skin. These patches are often accompanied by itching and burning, and may be located anywhere on the body. Erythema multiforme typically occurs in response to an infection or medication, and is not contagious from person to person. It can be treated with antihistamines, topical steroids, and other medications depending on the severity of the condition.

Nipah virus encephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the brain, has a material basis in the Nipah virus, which is transmitted by direct contact with sick persons or animals, or their contaminated tissues. The infection can cause symptoms such as dizziness, drowsiness, altered consciousness, disorientation, and coma.

Argentine hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has material basis in the Junin virus, which is transmitted by rodents, specifically Calomys musculinus. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, fatigue, malaise, leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, and hemorrhagic manifestations.

Bolivian hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has symptoms such as fever, headache, fatigue, myalgia, arthralgia, and bleeding from various body parts including the oral and nasal mucosa, bronchopulmonary, gastrointestinal, and genitourinary tracts. It is caused by a member of the Mammarenavirus family called Machupo virus which is transmitted by vesper mice (Calomys callosus).

Venezuelan hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has material basis in Mammarenavirus guanaritoense and is transmitted by cotton rat, Sigmodon alstoni or cane mouse, Zygodontomys brevicauda. It has symptoms such as fever, headache, myalgia, sore throat, weakness, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, convulsions, epistaxis, bleeding gums, hematemesis, melena, and menorrhagia.

Brazilian hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has material basis in the Mammarenavirus brazilense and is transmitted by rodents. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, eye redness, fatigue, dizziness, muscle aches, loss of strength, and bleeding under the skin, internal organs, or from body orifices like the mouth, eyes or ears.

Chapare hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that has a material basis in the Mammarenavirus chapareense. The disease is characterized by symptoms such as headache, joint pain, muscle pain, vomiting, shock, and bleeding.

Whitewater arroyo hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease characterized by fever, headaches, myalgia, and hemorrhagic manifestations. It is caused by the Mammarenavirus whitewaterense, which is transmitted by white-throated woodrats (Neotoma albigula).

Korean hemorrhagic fever is a type of hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome. It is transmitted by the eurasian field mouse, Apodemus agrarius or the norwegian rat, Rattus norvegicus. Symptoms include headache, back pain, abdominal pain, fever, chills, nausea, blurred vision, flushing of the face, redness of the eyes, rash, low blood pressure, acute shock, vascular leakage, and acute kidney failure.

nephropathia epidemica is a type of hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome, which has material basis in Orthohantavirus puumalaense and is transmitted by bank voles. It presents symptoms such as headache, nausea, back pain, vomiting, myalgia, abdominal pain, internal hemorrhage, and renal failure.

Lujo hemorrhagic fever is a type of viral infectious disease that causes severe bleeding and other symptoms. It is caused by the Lujo virus, which has a material basis in the blood. The disease can result in serious health problems if not treated promptly.

epstein barr virus hepatitis is a type of viral hepatitis that results in inflammation in the liver and has a material basis in human gammaherpesvirus 4. It can cause symptoms such as headache, fatigue, fever, abdominal pain, nausea, and jaundice.

Swine influenza, also known as swine flu, is a type of influenza that affects both pigs and humans. It has a material basis in either the Influenza C virus or one of the Influenza A virus subtypes (H1N1, H1N2, H3N1, H3N2, and H2N3). The infection is transmitted through direct contact with infected pigs. When humans are affected by swine influenza, they may experience a range of symptoms including fever, lethargy, lack of appetite, coughing, runny nose, sore throat, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.

Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome (LEMS) is a rare autoimmune disorder that affects the neuromuscular junction, resulting in muscle weakness and fatigue. It is characterized by an autoimmune attack against voltage-gated calcium channels (VGCC) on the presynaptic motor nerve terminal, leading to abnormalities in the release of acetylcholine (ACh). This can cause muscle weakness, especially in the face, arms, and legs, as well as fatigue, dry mouth, and other symptoms. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have LEMS, as it can be a serious condition that requires treatment.

Polycystic echinococcosis is a type of disease that affects the liver. It is caused by the larvae of Echinococcus vogeli or Echinococcus oligarthrus. The disease has the exact synonyms of human polycystic hydatid disease and neotropical echinococcosis.

Selective IgM deficiency disease is a type of dysgammaglobulinemia, which refers to the condition where one or more types of antibodies in the blood are low. In this case, it's specifically IgM that is lacking. This can make individuals more susceptible to certain infections and illnesses, as they may not have adequate protection against them. It's important for those affected by this condition to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage it effectively and ensure proper treatment.

Primary amebic meningoencephalitis (PAM) is a type of parasitic protozoa infectious disease that involves infection of the central nervous system caused by Naegleria fowleri. The symptoms include headache, nausea, rigidity of the neck muscles, vomiting, delirium, seizures and coma. It is also known as Naegleria fowleri infection.

Granulomatous amebic encephalitis is a type of primary amebic meningoencephalitis. It is caused by the parasite Acanthamoeba or Balamuthia mandrillaris and can result in infection of the brain, leading to symptoms such as headaches, altered mental status, and focal neurologic deficit that progresses over several weeks to death. It has an exact synonym of Acanthamoeba encephalitis, Acanthamoeba granulomatous encephalitis, Granulomatous Amebic Encephalitis due to Acanthamoeba and granulomatous amoebic encephalitis.

Philophthalmiasis is an eye disease caused by a parasite known as Philophthalmus species. It can present with symptoms such as follicular conjunctivitis and superficial keratitis in the external eye, or mild edema with minimal cellular reaction in the sub-conjunctival area of the eye.

Coenurosis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection by metacestode larval stage (coenurus) of Taenia multiceps or Taenia serialis. Coenuri in the skin or subcutaneous tissue present as painless nodules, which manifest on the trunk, sclera, subconjuctiva, neck, shoulders, head and limbs. Coenuri in the central nervous system may cause headache, fever, vomiting, nerve palsies, jacksonian epilepsy, pachymeningitis, obstructive or communicating hydrocephalus, and intracranial arteritis with transient hemiparesis. Coenuri in the eye cause both intraocular and orbital infections.

Mesocestoidiasis is a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection with the cestode Mesocestoides lineatus. This leads to symptoms such as nausea, diarrhea, abdominal discomfort, and vomiting. It has a precise definition as "A parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves parasitic cestode infection caused by Mesocestoides lineatus resulting in nausea, diarrhea, abdominal discomfort and vomiting."

acanthocephaliasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection of the intestine caused by thorny-headed worms Macracanthorhynchus or Moniliformis moniliformis. The infection has symptom abdominal pain, has symptom distension, has symptom fever, has symptom decreased appetite, has symptom nausea, has symptom vomiting, has symptom weight loss, has symptom diarrhea, and has symptom constipation or has symptom bloody stools.

angiostrongyliasis is a type of central nervous system disease characterized by inflammation, pain, and paralysis. It is caused by the infection of the Angiostrongylus cantonensis or Angiostrongylus costaricensis, which are species of roundworms that live in the intestines of rats. The disease can affect both humans and animals, and its symptoms may include fever, headache, nausea, vomiting, muscle pain, stiffness, and paralysis. Treatment typically involves medications to reduce inflammation and alleviate symptoms, as well as supportive care to manage complications such as respiratory failure or neurological deficits. Prevention measures include reducing contact between humans and rats, sealing off rat burrows, and using pesticides to control rat populations.

Baylisascariasis is a rare and potentially life-threatening parasitic infection caused by the larvae of Baylisascaris procyonis, which can infect various parts of the body including the intestine, brain, spinal cord, eye, and sometimes the heart. Symptoms may include fever, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhea, seizures, blindness, and paralysis. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or someone you know has been infected with Baylisascariasis.

Dioctophymiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves parasitic infection by the nematode Dioctophyme renale in humans after eating undercooked food. The larvae are found in the subcutaneous nodules and kidneys.

Thelaziasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that affects the eyes. It is caused by a nematode worm called Thelazia callipaeda and can cause various symptoms such as inflammation, lacrimation, photophobia, edema, conjunctivitis, and even blindness in severe cases.

tungiasis is a type of parasitic ectoparasitic infectious disease that is an inflammatory skin disease caused by the parasitic infestation of the female chigoe flea, Tunga penetrans in animals and humans. The symptoms include skin inflammation, severe pain, itching, and a lesion at the site of infection that is characterized by a black dot at the center of a swollen red lesion, surrounded by a white halo.

ophthalmomyiasis is a type of myiasis, which is the medical term for when birds build nests in or around the eyes and ears of humans. This can cause discomfort, pain, and even long-term damage if not treated properly. Ophthalmomyiasis specifically involves parasitic infestation of Oestrus ovis larvae in the eye, causing severe irritation, edema, and pain. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition to avoid further complications.

trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis is a type of infection caused by the bacterium Trichomonas vaginalis.
trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis is a type of sexually transmitted disease (STD).
trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis has symptoms such as abnormal discharge, itching, and irritation.
trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis can be treated with antibiotics.
trichomonas vaginalis trichomoniasis is more common in women than men.

Trichomonas tenax is a species of single-celled protozoan parasite that causes trichomoniasis, a type of sexually transmitted infection. Trichomonas tenax can be spread through various means, including oral droplets, by kissing or eating utensils. When the parasite is aspirated into the lungs, it can cause bronchopulmonary trichomoniasis. Additionally, Trichomonas tenax can also cause periodontitis when it infects the gums and other structures in the mouth.

Basidiobolomycosis is a type of subcutaneous mycosis that involves chronic inflammatory or granulomatous fungal infection of the subcutaneous tissue of the limbs, chest, back or buttocks caused by Basidiobolus ranarum. It presents with subcutaneous nodules that develop into massive, firm, indurated, painless swellings which are freely movable over the underlying muscle, but are attached to the skin and may become hyperpigmented.

Conidiobolomycosis is a type of subcutaneous mycosis characterized by chronic inflammatory or granulomatous fungal infections caused by Conidiobolus species. It affects the nasal submucosa and presents as polyps or palpable restricted subcutaneous masses, leading to symptoms such as nasal obstruction, drainage, and sinus pain. The development of subcutaneous nodules occurs in the nasal and perinasal regions.

Penicilliosis is a type of opportunistic mycosis caused by the fungus Penicillium marneffei. It can result in systemic infection and has symptoms such as fever, anemia, weight loss, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, respiratory signs, and skin lesions.

Fusariosis is a type of opportunistic mycosis that involves localized or hematogenously disseminated fungal infection by Fusarium solani or Fusarium oxysporum. It is characterized by skin lesions in neutropenic patients and indolent cellulitis or soft-tissue necrosis in immunocompromised patients at the site of trauma.

Trichosporonosis is a type of fungal infection caused by the fungus Trichosporon. It can result in disseminated infections and cause the formation of nontender erythematous nodules on various parts of the body.

Parasitic ichthyosporea infectious disease is a type of parasitic infection caused by the members of the class Ichthyosporea. These organisms are typically parasites of fish and other animals, and they can cause a variety of health problems in their hosts. Symptoms of parasitic ichthyosporea infectious disease may include fever, diarrhea, vomiting, weight loss, and skin lesions. In severe cases, it can lead to death. Treatment typically involves antiparasitic drugs and supportive care to manage symptoms and prevent complications.

Primary systemic mycosis is a type of infection that occurs when fungi can overcome the defenses of the human body, and it results from an infection located within the human body. This type of mycosis has a material basis in fungi.

The primary deep pathogens usually gain access to the host via the respiratory tract.

Aniseikonia is a refractive error where the sizes of objects are perceived differently in each eye, causing double vision or blurred vision. It can be caused by a variety of factors such as genetics, trauma, and certain medical conditions. Treatment options for aniseikonia include glasses, contact lenses, and surgical procedures depending on the severity of the condition.

Alkhurma Hemorrhagic Fever is a viral infectious disease that has material basis in the Alkhumra Hemorrhagic Fever virus. It is transmitted by Ornithodoros savignyi tick bite, ingestion of unpasteurized camel milk, or entry via skin wound. The symptoms include headache, joint pain, muscle pain, vomiting, thrombocytopenia, and hemorrhagic fever.

Congenital hypothyroidism is a type of physical disorder where the thyroid gland does not develop properly in an infant during pregnancy. This results in an underactive thyroid gland, which can lead to developmental delays and other health problems if left untreated. It is essential for infants born with congenital hypothyroidism to receive proper treatment, including lifelong replacement therapy with synthetic thyroid hormones, to ensure normal growth and development.

Lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by abnormalities affecting the lacrimal and salivary glands and ducts, ears, teeth and fingers and toes. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the tyrosine kinase domain of the FGFR2 gene on chromosome 10q26. This syndrome is also known as Levy-Hollister Syndrome or Lacrimo-auriculo-dento-digital syndrome 1.

Enlarged vestibular aqueduct (EVA) is a type of congenital inner ear condition that affects the vestibular aqueduct, which is responsible for carrying balance- and equilibrium-related information from the inner ear to the brain. It occurs when this canal is larger than usual or does not close properly during fetal development. As a result, the fluid in the inner ear may become too much, causing damage to the hair cells that help detect movement and maintain balance. This can lead to progressive hearing loss and dizziness. EVA is typically diagnosed with a VEMP test, which measures the strength of the vestibular muscles responsible for balance and eye movements. Treatment options include hearing aids or cochlear implants, depending on the severity of the condition.

Bradyopsia is a condition where the eyes have difficulty adapting to changes in light. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means it is passed down through families and can be caused by mutations in specific genes. The term "bradyopsia" comes from Greek roots meaning "slow seeing," as patients with this condition may have difficulty adjusting their vision to different lighting conditions. Prolonged electroretinal response suppression (PERS) is a more precise way of describing the condition, but bradyopsia is still commonly used in everyday language.

Hypophosphatemia is a medical condition characterized by an abnormally low level of phosphorus in the blood. It can cause symptoms such as bone pain, weakness, and muscle cramps due to the body's inability to utilize phosphate effectively. Additionally, it may also lead to osteomalacia (softening of bones), osteoarthritis, and other skeletal problems if left untreated.

primary bacterial infectious disease can be caused by a variety of different types of bacteria.
Some examples include salmonella, staphylococcus, and E. coli. These bacteria can cause illnesses such as food poisoning, staph infections, and urinary tract infections. It is important to practice good hygiene and seek medical attention if you suspect you have a primary bacterial infectious disease.

Commensal bacterial infectious disease refers to a type of bacterial infection where the pathogenic bacteria are part of the normal human flora. This means that these bacteria are typically present on the skin and mucous membranes without causing any harm or issues. However, if there is a breach in the body's natural defenses, such as through accidental injury, surgery, or underlying metabolic or infectious disorders, these bacteria can multiply and cause an infection. Examples of commensal bacterial infectious diseases include urinary tract infections caused by Escherichia coli and skin infections caused by Staphylococcus aureus.

opportunistic bacterial infectious disease is a type of bacterial infection that occurs in individuals whose immune systems are weakened or compromised, such as those with HIV/AIDS. Examples include tuberculosis (TB), pneumonia, and urinary tract infections (UTIs). These types of infections can be more severe and difficult to treat than infections caused by healthy individuals due to the weakened state of their immune systems. It is important for those with compromised immune systems to seek medical attention promptly if they experience symptoms of an opportunistic bacterial infectious disease.

Foodborne botulism is a type of botulism that is transmitted by ingestion of food contaminated with preformed toxins produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. It can cause a range of symptoms, including double vision (diplopia), difficulty speaking and swallowing (dysarthria

Wound botulism is a type of botulism that is caused by the toxins produced by Clostridium botulinum, which can be transmitted through contact with contaminated wounds. It has a material basis in the bacteria Clostridium botulinum and its various forms, such as B, E, and F. These toxins are produced when the spores of Clostridium botulinum come into contact with open wounds and anaerobic environments, leading to the reproduction of the bacteria and the production of the toxins.

Infant botulism is a type of botulism that involves toxins produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and can be transmitted through ingestion of contaminated food. It commonly presents with symptoms such as constipation, lethargy, difficulty feeding, muscle weakness, and drooping eyelids. The infection is typically treated with antitoxins and supportive care to alleviate symptoms and prevent complications.
Glandular tularemia is a specific type of tularemia that causes swelling in the regional lymph glands.
Typhoidal Tularemia is a type of tularemia that results in bacteremia and has symptoms such as fever, chills, myalgia, malaise, and weight loss.
Hereditary nonpapillary renal cell carcinoma is a subtype of hereditary renal cell carcinoma characterized by the loss of 3p13-pter sequences.

Carrion's disease, also known as Oroya fever, is a type of bartonellosis characterized by the infection of endothelial cells or red blood cells. It is transmitted through sandflies and has acute and chronic phases. The acute phase is marked by severe hemolytic anemia and immunosuppression, while the chronic phase results in verruga peruana lesions that may ulcerate and bleed. Another name for this disease is Carrion disease.

Certainly! Complement factor I (CFI) deficiency is a type of complement deficiency that results in recurrent pyogenic bacterial infections due to the deficiency of complement component 3. It can also be referred to as C3 inactivator deficiency or complement component 3 inactivator deficiency, but "CFI deficiency" is a more common and concise term used to describe this condition.

Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is a type of autosomal genetic disease that affects the large intestine. It is characterized by the development of numerous benign growths, called polyps, in the lining of the colon and rectum. These polyps can become cancerous over time if left untreated. FAP is caused by a mutation in the APC gene, which is inherited from one or both parents. It is important for individuals with FAP to undergo regular screening and surveillance to detect and remove any precancerous polyps before they become cancerous.

Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS) is a neurological disorder that affects the legs and causes unpleasant sensations such as creeping, crawling or tingling. It can also cause an intense urge to move the legs, which can lead to constant movement during sleep. RLS can be caused by various factors including genetics, pregnancy, iron deficiency, and certain medications. There is no cure for RLS, but symptoms can be managed with lifestyle changes, medication, and other treatments.

Stevens-Johnson syndrome is a rare, acute, sometimes life-threatening skin disorder. It is characterized by a fever and the shedding of the top layer of skin on areas of the body, such as the face, chest, back, and extremities. The condition can cause painful blisters to form, which may rupture and lead to severe pain, infections, and scarring. It is often a complication of medications or an underlying illness, such as glandular fever. Treatment typically involves managing symptoms with over-the-counter pain relievers, cool baths, and moist compresses. In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary for intravenous fluids and other supportive care.

Xeroderma pigmentosum (XP) is a group of genetic disorders that are characterized by an abnormality in the ability to repair DNA damage caused by exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation. It is a type of autosomal recessive inherited disease, which means that it can only be passed on by a parent who has the gene for the condition. XP can cause skin to become dry and wrinkled, and in severe cases, it can lead to cancer.

nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of skin condition characterized by the development of thick, dry, scaly patches on the palms and soles. It can be inherited or acquired and may be caused by exposure to sunlight or other environmental factors. Treatment options include topical creams, light therapy, and surgical removal in severe cases.

Hailey Hailey disease (also known as Benign Familial Pemphigus) is a type of autosomal dominant skin disorder characterized by recurring blisters forming in the folds and creases of the skin. It is caused by mutations in the ATP2C1 gene, which leads to a loss of adhesion within the skin. Hailey Hailey disease is also known as Benign Chronic Pemphigus and Pemphigus, Benign Familial.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 2a (MEN2A) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of medullary carcinoma of the thyroid, pheochromocytoma, hyperparathyroidism, and occasionally cutaneous lichen amyloidosis. It is also known as MEN2 or MEN2A, and it has a high risk of developing other endocrine tumors such as paragangliomas and phaeochromocytomas.

Arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy (ARVC) is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy that affects the right ventricle of the heart. It is characterized by hypokinetic areas involving the free wall of the right ventricle, with fibrofatty replacement of the right ventricular myocardium, and associated arrhythmias originating in the right ventricle with limited or no involvement of the left ventricle. ARVC is also known as Arrhythmogenic Right Ventricular Dysplasia (ARVD), ARVC cardiomyopathy, and right ventricular ACM.

Asperger syndrome, also known as Asperger's, is a neurodevelopmental disorder that falls on the autism spectrum. It is characterized by difficulties in social interaction and restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior and interests. Individuals with Asperger's typically have better language skills and cognitive development than those with other autism spectrum disorders, such as classic autism.

Fatal familial insomnia (FFI) is a rare and aggressive form of prion disease that affects the human brain. It is characterized by severe insomnia, hallucinations, dementia, and ultimately death. The disease primarily affects the thalamus, which is responsible for regulating sleep patterns.

There are no known treatments or cures for FFI, and it has a poor prognosis. Symptoms usually appear within six months of onset and progress rapidly, leading to complete mental and physical deterioration within a year. The disease affects primarily members of the same family, with an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.

It is important for individuals who suspect they may have FFI or are concerned about their risk to consult with a medical professional for further evaluation and guidance. Early diagnosis and intervention can be critical in managing symptoms and improving quality of life.

Andersen Tawil Syndrome is a type of long QT syndrome, which is a group of cardiac disorders that affect the heart's electrical activity. Andersen Tawil Syndrome is characterized by an abnormal curvature of the fingers called clinodactyly, micrognathia (an unusually small lower jaw), and low-set ears. It is caused by a mutation in the KCNJ2 gene, which disrupts the rhythm of the heart's lower chambers and can result in ventricular arrhythmia. Andersen Tawil Syndrome is also known as Potassium-Sensitive Cardiodysrhythmic Type or Long QT syndrome 7.

Muibrey Nanism is a rare genetic disorder characterized by growth failure and developmental delay in various body parts. It affects both males and females equally, with an equal distribution across all ethnic groups. The condition is caused by mutations in the TRIM37 gene on the X chromosome, which leads to the production of abnormal proteins that interfere with normal muscle development.

The symptoms of Muibrey Nanism can vary widely among individuals, but often include short stature, weak muscles, liver and kidney problems, heart defects, and vision problems. The disorder can also affect the brain, leading to intellectual disability and behavioral issues.

There is no cure for Muibrey Nanism, but treatment may focus on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. This may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, and medications to manage pain or seizures. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct heart defects or other problems.

Early diagnosis is critical for managing Muibrey Nanism effectively. Parents of affected children should work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an individualized care plan that addresses the unique needs of their child.<|end_of_textarea|>

Danon disease is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the heart and skeletal muscles. It is caused by mutations in the LAMP2 gene, which encodes for a protein involved in the transport of lipids within lysosomes. The condition is inherited in an X-linked dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene is sufficient to cause the disease in males, while females typically require two copies (one from each parent) to develop symptoms.
The main features of Danon disease include cardiomyopathy (weakness and enlargement of the heart), skeletal myopathy (muscle weakness and pain), and intellectual disability. The condition can also present with other features such as short stature, brachydactyly (abnormal shortening of the fingers and toes), and distinct facial features.
Treatment for Danon disease usually focuses on managing symptoms, but there is no cure at this time. Supportive care may include medications to manage heart failure or hypertension, physical therapy to improve muscle strength, and a healthy diet to maintain proper nutrition.
It's important to note that Danon disease can be diagnosed in individuals with symptoms of cardiomyopathy, skeletal myopathy, and intellectual disability, even if they do not have the specific LAMP2 gene mutation associated with this condition. A thorough genetic evaluation and consultation with a specialized medical professional is recommended for proper diagnosis and management.

Frasier syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects both males and females. It is characterized by gonadal dysgenesis, which means underdevelopment of the male reproductive organs or failure of the female reproductive organs to develop properly. Additionally, individuals with Frasier syndrome may experience progressive focal segmental glomerulonephropathy, a type of kidney disease, and an increased risk of developing certain types of cancer, specifically urogenital cancers such as testicular or ovarian cancer. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that having one affected copy of the gene is enough to increase the risk of developing the condition.

Usher Syndrome is a genetic condition that affects the ears and eyes. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that it can be passed down from generation to generation in families. The hearing loss typically begins during childhood or adolescence, while the visual impairment may not become apparent until later in life. The condition is named after Dr. Charles Usher, who first described the syndrome in 1914. There are three types of Usher Syndrome: Type I, Type II, and Type III. Each type has different genetic causes and can affect hearing and vision to varying degrees.

Familial Partial Lipodystrophy, also known as Dunnigan Syndrome or Koberling-Dunnigan Syndrome, is a type of partial lipodystrophy characterized by abnormal subcutaneous adipose tissue distribution beginning in late childhood or early adult life.

Mucosulfatidosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by leukodystrophy, ichthyosis, skeletal abnormalities and shortened life expectancy. It has a material basis in mutation in the SUMF1 gene, which results in deficiency in multiple sulfatase enzymes. The exact synonyms for this condition include Sulfatidosis, Juvenile, Austin Type, and multiple sulfatase deficiency disease.

Infantile Refsum disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of fats in the body. It is characterized by neurological impairment, intellectual disability, hepatosplenomegaly (enlarged liver and spleen), and ichthyosis (scaly skin). The condition occurs due to a deficiency in an enzyme called PEX, which is responsible for breaking down harmful substances called toxins that build up in the body. This leads to the accumulation of very long chain fatty acids and phytanic acid, causing the symptoms associated with Infantile Refsum disease. The exact synonym of this condition is infantile phytanic acid storage disease.

X-linked dominant hypophosphatemic rickets, also known as Vitamin D-resistant rickets, is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to regulate phosphate levels. This condition is caused by mutations in the PHEX gene on the X chromosome, which leads to increased levels of FGF-23 (phosphatonin), a hormone that regulates phosphate levels in the blood. As a result, this disrupts normal bone mineralization and can cause rickets, a condition characterized by soft and weak bones.
This type of rickets is inherited in an X-linked dominant manner, meaning that only one copy of the gene is needed for the condition to be expressed. It can also be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Treatment typically involves supplementation with vitamin D and calcium to help improve bone health.

White sponge nevus is a type of skin disease that is characterized by a defect in the normal process of keratinization of the mucosa. It is also known as hereditary mucosal leukokeratosis and white sponge nevus of Cannon.

Pachyonychia congenita is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by hypertrophic nails and hyperkeratosis of the hands and feet. It has a material basis in gene mutations that result in changes in keratin. It is also known as Jadassohn-Lewandowsky Syndrome, Pachyonychia Congenita Type 1, and Jackson-Lewandowski Syndrome.

Gitelman syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the kidneys and is characterized by a loss of salt in the urine due to mutations in genes involved in the reabsorption of sodium. It can cause symptoms such as low blood pressure, muscle weakness, and joint pain. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that both copies of the gene must be inherited from parents for a person to develop the condition.

Brugada syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal electrocardiogram (ECG) findings and an increased risk of sudden cardiac death. It is also known by several other names, including Bangungut, Brugada type idiopathic ventricular fibrillation, Dream disease, Pokkuri death syndrome, SUNDS, and sudden unexplained nocturnal death syndrome (SUNDS).

Mevalonic aciduria, also known as Mevalonate Kinase Deficiency, is a type of peroxisomal disease that is characterized by cortical atrophy, microcephaly, dysmorphic facies, muscular hypotonia and intellectual disability. It occurs when there is a mutation in the MVK gene, which leads to deficiency of mevalonate kinase and impaired cholesterol biosynthesis.

Lissencephaly is a type of congenital nervous system abnormality that occurs due to the absence of folds in the cerebral cortex, which is caused by defective neuronal migration during the 12th to 24th weeks of gestation. It is characterized by the underdevelopment or absence of the cerebral cortex, leading to a smooth or gyri-less appearance on imaging studies. Lissencephaly can lead to a variety of neurological symptoms and physical abnormalities, including developmental delays, seizures, microcephaly (small head size), and motor skills problems.

Periventricular nodular heterotopia is a congenital nervous system abnormality in which neurons do not migrate properly during fetal brain development. It results in the presence of non-native tissue, or "heterotopia," in the periventricular (around the ventricles) areas of the brain. This condition can cause seizures and other neurological symptoms, but is generally not life-threatening. Treatment may involve medication to control seizures or surgery to remove the affected tissue.

Buruli ulcer disease is a primary bacterial infectious disease caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium ulcerans. It results in skin or subcutaneous tissue infections and can be transmitted through insect bites, with a toxin called mycolactone produced by the bacterium causing subcutaneous fat necrosis and immune system suppression. Symptoms include nodules, which are painless, mobile swellings in the skin. Buruli ulcer disease has several synonyms including Bairnsdale ulcer, Daintree ulcer, Mossman ulcer, Searl ulcer, and Searle's ulcer.

Sertoli cell-only syndrome, also known as germinal cell aplasia or del Castillo syndrome, is a type of male infertility. It is characterized by the absence of sperm in the semen (azospermia) without any abnormalities in sexual development. This condition can be caused by genetic factors, exposure to certain drugs, or other medical conditions. Treatment options may include medications, surgery, or assisted reproductive technologies such as in vitro fertilization (IVF). It is important for individuals with this condition to consult with a healthcare professional to determine the best course of action based on their specific needs and circumstances.

Juvenile myelomonocytic leukemia (JMML) is a subtype of Myelodysplastic/Myeloproliferative Neoplasm (MDS/MPN) characterized by the uncontrolled growth of monocytes. It typically affects children and young adults, with onset occurring before age 20.

Hyperphosphatemia is a medical condition characterized by an excess of phosphorus in the blood. It occurs when there is an imbalance in the body's ability to regulate phosphate levels, either due to dietary intake or metabolic processes.
In some cases, hyperphosphatemia can lead to abnormal deposits of phosphate and calcium in joints and soft tissues, which may cause pain, stiffness, and reduced mobility.
Hyperphosphatemia is typically diagnosed through blood tests that measure the level of phosphorus in the body. Treatment for hyperphosphatemia usually involves reducing dietary phosphorus intake and managing any underlying medical conditions that may be contributing to the imbalance in phosphate levels. In severe cases, medications such as phosphate binders or dialysis may be required to help regulate blood phosphorus levels.
Hyperphosphatemia can be caused by a variety of factors, including kidney disease, liver disease, gastrointestinal disorders, and certain medications. It is important to work with a healthcare professional to determine the underlying cause and develop an appropriate treatment plan.

Wolf-Hirschhorn syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that occurs due to a deletion of part of chromosome 4. It affects many parts of the body, including the face, hands, and feet. The severity of the condition can vary greatly from one individual to another. Some people with this disorder may have mild symptoms, while others may be more severely affected. Common features of Wolf-Hirschhorn syndrome include distinct facial features such as a large head, small jaw, underdeveloped teeth and tongue, low muscle tone (hypotonia), and intellectual disability. The condition is typically diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can have significant impacts on the individual's development and daily life.

Aspartylglucosaminuria is a type of lysosomal storage disease that affects the body's ability to break down glycoproteins. It is characterized by delayed speech at 2-3 years of age and is caused by mutations in the AGA gene, which results in the absence or shortage of the aspartylglucosaminidase enzyme in lysosomes. The condition has synonyms such as aspartylglycosaminuria, glycosylasparaginase deficiency, and is also known as MESH:D054880.

Antley-Bixler syndrome, also known as Trapezoid-Cephalic dysostosis or MESH: D054882, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by congenital malformations and deformities affecting the majority of the skeleton, including the skull, face, hands, feet, and spine. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. The disorder primarily affects boys, although it can also occur in girls.
Symptoms usually become apparent at birth or during early childhood and may include:
* Abnormal skull shape
* Hip dysplasia
* Scoliosis or other spinal abnormalities
* Short stature
* Delayed growth
* Limb asymmetry
* Joint problems, such as arthritis or carpal tunnel syndrome
Treatment for Antley-Bixler syndrome typically focuses on managing the symptoms and improving quality of life. This may include:
* Corrective surgery to address skull deformities, hip dysplasia, or other skeletal abnormalities
* Physical therapy to improve mobility and strength
* Medication to manage pain, inflammation, or other symptoms
* Monitoring growth and development with regular check-ups for early intervention if needed.
It's important to note that the severity of Antley-Bixler syndrome can vary greatly from person to person, and some individuals may have mild symptoms while others may experience more severe complications.

Campomelic dysplasia is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the extremities. It is caused by a mutation in the SOX9 gene on chromosome 17q24. The condition presents at birth with congenital shortness and bowing of long tubular bones, especially in the lower extremities, as well as hypoplastic scapulae, narrow iliac wings, and nonmineralized thoracic pedicles. It is considered as an autosomal dominant disease, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the condition.

Farber lipogranulomatosis is a type of lipid storage disease that affects the body's ability to break down certain fats. It occurs due to a deficiency in the enzyme ceramidase, which leads to an accumulation of sphingolipids in the body. This can cause a range of symptoms, including abnormalities in swallowing, cognition, joint function, and the central nervous system. The disease is also known by other names, such as Farber disease, N-laurylsphingosine deacylase deficiency, and acid ceramidase deficiency.

Muir-Torre Syndrome (MTS) is a rare genetic disorder that belongs to the category of Lynch Syndrome. It is characterized by an increased risk for developing certain types of cancer, most commonly involving the gastrointestinal tract, genitourinary system, and skin. The underlying cause of MTS is mutations in specific DNA mismatch repair genes, which are responsible for maintaining the accuracy of DNA replication in our cells. When these genes are mutated, it leads to a higher risk of developing cancer due to the accumulation of DNA damage in the affected cells.

Loeys-Dietz Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. It is characterized by an increased risk of aortic aneurysm and dissection, elongated limbs, hypertelorism (widely spaced eyes), bifid uvula (a split or forked tongue), and easy skin bruising. The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the faulty gene is sufficient to cause the disorder. It is caused by mutations in the TGFB3 gene, which encodes a protein that plays a crucial role in the development and maintenance of connective tissue.
Erythrokeratodermia variabilis is a type of monogenic skin disease.

Yellow nail syndrome is a rare condition that is characterized by the accumulation of protein-rich fluid (lymph) in the soft layers of tissue under the skin, which can lead to pleural effusions, lymphedema, and yellow dystrophic nails. The nails affected by this syndrome are loose or detached and grow slowly. It is important to note that while it has been described as a type of nail disease, it is actually a systemic condition with skin and nail manifestations.

Costello Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects many different parts of the body. It is caused by mutations in the HRAS gene, which is located on the seventh chromosome. People with Costello Syndrome often have distinct facial features, such as a wide-set eyes and a prominent jaw. They may also have other physical characteristics like short stature, webbed fingers and toes, and a high-pitched voice. In addition to these physical traits, individuals with Costello Syndrome may experience developmental delays, learning difficulties, and behavioral issues. The syndrome can also increase the risk of certain medical conditions, such as heart defects and tumors. Overall, Costello Syndrome is a complex disorder that requires careful management and support from healthcare professionals to address its various physical, cognitive, and emotional needs.

Donohue syndrome, also known as Leprechaunism, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects several body systems. It is characterized by the presence of protuberant and low-set ears, flaring nostrils, thick lips, enlarged secondary sex organs, overwhelming insulin resistance, and other abnormalities such as those caused by mutations within the INSR gene that affect the insulin receptor. It is important to note that Donohue syndrome has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is not just a "type of something" but rather a specific diagnosis with distinct symptoms and characteristics.

Carney Complex is a term used to describe a group of disorders that are characterized by the presence of myxomas, which are non-cancerous tumors made up of thick, sticky blood vessels. These tumors can cause problems with circulation and may be painful. Carney Complex also includes skin pigmentation patterns (also known as "patches") and endocrine overactivity.
Carney Syndrome is a term that is sometimes used to describe this group of disorders, although it is not as widely accepted as Carney Complex. Some people prefer to use the term Carney Syndrome because they feel that it more accurately reflects the diverse range of symptoms and features that can be present in these disorders.
Regardless of whether someone uses the term Carney Complex or Carney Syndrome, it is important to note that these disorders are inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This means that a person only needs to inherit one copy of the gene for the disorder to develop. In some cases, this can result in milder symptoms, but it is still important for people with a family history of Carney Complex or related disorders to be evaluated by a healthcare professional.
monilethrix is a type of hair disease characterized by short, easily broken hair that results in alopecia and has material basis in mutations in genes for type II hair cortex keratins.

Alstrom syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organs in the body, primarily causing blindness due to congenital retinal dystrophy. It also commonly causes obesity and sensorineural hearing loss. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that it requires the presence of two copies of the gene for its expression. Alstrom syndrome can be caused by mutations in the ALMS1 gene.

Netherton Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin, eyes and mucous membranes. It is caused by mutations in the SPINK5 gene, which results in a reduced capacity to inhibit serine proteases expressed in the skin. Symptoms include chronic skin inflammation, trichorrhexis invaginata (hair breaking off from the root), atopic dermatitis and other skin conditions. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Weill-Marchesani Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects several parts of the body, including the face, hands, and feet. It is characterized by short stature, brachycephaly (a flattened facial profile), and other facial abnormalities. People with this syndrome may also have brachydactyly (short fingers and toes), joint stiffness, distinctive ocular abnormalities, and other physical features. The exact cause of Weill-Marchesani Syndrome is unknown, but it is believed to be inherited in an autosomal manner. It has also been referred to as GEMSS syndrome, Marchesani-Weill Syndrome, Mesodermal Dysmorphodystrophy, Congenital Spherophakia Brachymorphia Syndrome, and congenital mesodermal dystrophy.

Barth syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects cardiac and skeletal muscles, as well as the liver. It is caused by mutations in the TAF1 gene, which is located on the X chromosome. The condition can cause severe symptoms from an early age, including heart problems, weakness, and joint pain. There is currently no cure for Barth syndrome, but treatments are available to help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

Liddle Syndrome is a type of renal tubular transport disease characterized by hypertension and hypokalemia caused by dysregulation of epithelial sodium channels leading to overexpression of the channel. It has an exact synonym Liddle's Syndrome, and another name for this condition is Pseudoaldosteronism.

epidemic typhus is a type of illness that affects people.
epidemic typhus is a type of illness that can be caused by the bacterium Rickettsia prowazekii.
epidemic typhus is a type of illness that is transmitted through contact with an infected person or animal, such as a human body louse (Pediculus humanus corporis).
epidemic typhus is a type of illness that has symptoms like high fever, delirium, cough and a rash.
epidemic typhus is a type of illness that can have severe consequences if not treated properly.
epidemic typhus has the ability to be life-threatening, especially if it is left untreated.
epidemic typhus is a dangerous disease that people need to be aware of and take precautions against.
epidemic typhus is a serious illness that requires medical attention and treatment.
epidemic typhus is not something to be taken lightly, and people should seek help if they think they have it.

endemic typhus is a type of typhus that has material basis in either Rickettsia felis or Rickettsia typhi, which are transmitted by fleas (Xenopsylla cheopis). It commonly presents with symptoms such as nausea, rash, headache, fever, chills, myalgia, and cough.
Aneruptive fever is a type of spotted fever that has material basis in Rickettsia helvetica and is transmitted by ticks (Ixodes sp). It has symptoms such as fever, headache, and myalgia.

Sennetsu fever, also known as Sennetsu ehrlichiosis, is a primary bacterial infectious disease that results in infection by the Neorickettsia sennetsu organism. It is transmitted through ingestion of raw or undercooked gray mullet fish infected with the trematodes. Symptoms include fever, malaise, anorexia, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, headache, backache, and myalgia.
Exanthem is a type of skin disease characterized by a rash that results from various causes such as bacteria, viruses, toxins, drugs, and autoimmune disorders.
bacterial exanthem is a type of infectious disease that is caused by bacteria. It usually presents with a red, blotchy rash on the skin and can be treated with antibiotics.

Early congenital syphilis is a type of congenital syphilis that is manifested during the first 3 months of life. It has symptoms such as skin lesions, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, failure to thrive, blood-stained nasal discharge, perioral fissures, meningitis, choroiditis, hydrocephalus, seizures, intellectual disability, osteochondritis, and pseudoparalysis. It is caused by the transmission of the syphilis bacterium from an infected mother to her unborn child during pregnancy or delivery. Early congenital syphilis is a serious condition that can cause long-term damage if not treated promptly and effectively.

Yes, that is correct. Multinodular goiter refers to a type of goiter where the thyroid gland is enlarged and has multiple nodules or lumps within it. These nodules can be benign or malignant in nature. It is also sometimes referred to as hyperplastic goiter.

Parenchymatous neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis, which occurs when chronic meningoencephalitis causes destruction of cortical parenchyma. It can present with symptoms such as irritability, difficulty concentrating, deterioration of memory, defective judgment, headaches, insomnia, fatigue, and lethargy.

Meningovascular neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis, which is a form of syphilis infection that has spread to the central nervous system. It is characterized by inflammation located in the arteries of the brain or spinal cord, and can cause a variety of symptoms including headache, neck stiffness, dizziness, behavioral abnormalities, poor concentration, memory loss, lassitude, insomnia, blurred vision, weakness and wasting of shoulder-girdle and arm muscles, slowly progressive leg weakness with urinary or fecal incontinence or both, and paralysis of the legs due to thrombosis of spinal arteries.

Exanthema subitum, also known as roseola infantum or the sixth disease, is a viral infectious disease that primarily affects infants and young children. It is caused by the Human herpesvirus 6 (HHV-6) or HHV-7, which are members of the family
Variola major is a severe form of smallpox, caused by the Variola virus. It can result in the formation of lesions on the skin and often leads to a fatal outcome.

Spinal polio, also known as poliomyelitis, is a type of paralytic disease that affects the spinal cord. It results in the destruction of motor neurons located in the spinal cord, which can lead to paralysis of the arms and legs. The disease has a material basis in one or more of the three types of the human poliovirus (1, 2, or 3), which are transmitted through the ingestion of food or water contaminated with feces or by direct contact with an infected individual's oral secretions.

Symptoms of spinal polio can include difficulty breathing and paralysis in the arms and legs. It is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have been exposed to this disease to receive proper treatment and prevent further spread.

Bulbospinal polio is a type of paralytic poliomyelitis that results in destruction located in motor neurons of the brainstem or located in motor neurons of the spinal cord, has_material_basis_in Human poliovirus 1, has_material_basis_in Human poliovirus 2, or has_material_basis_in Human poliovirus 3, which are transmitted by ingestion of food or water contaminated with feces, or transmitted by direct contact with the oral secretions. The infection causes symptoms such as difficulty breathing, difficulty swallowing, and paralysis of arms and legs.

Paralytic poliomyelitis is a type of central nervous system disease. It results from the destruction of motor neurons in the central nervous system, which are located in the area that controls voluntary movements such as muscle function. This virus has different strains and can be transmitted through contaminated food or water, or direct contact with an infected person's saliva. The symptoms include loss of reflexes, muscle spasms, and acute flaccid paralysis.

Nyong Nyong Fever is a viral infectious disease that is transmitted by the Anopheles gambiae and Anopheles funestus mosquitoes. It causes symptoms such as fever, arthralgia, rash, and lymphadenitis in the affected individual.

Barmah Forest virus disease is caused by the Barmah Forest virus, which is transmitted through mosquito bites. The infection can cause symptoms such as fever, arthralgia (pain and swelling in joints), and a rash.

Ross River virus disease is an illness caused by the Ross River virus, which is transmitted through the bites of certain mosquito species. Symptoms typically appear within 1 to 4 days after exposure and may include fever, joint pain, swelling, and a rash. The illness can last for several days or even weeks, and there is no specific treatment available other than symptom relief. Prevention measures include using insect repellent when outdoors in areas where the virus is known to be present and taking measures to reduce standing water sources that may attract mosquitoes.

Orpouche fever is a type of viral infectious disease that results in infection, has material basis in Oropouche virus, which is transmitted by biting midge Culicoides paraensis and has symptoms such as fever, chills, headache, anorexia, muscle pain, joint pain, and vomiting.

Balkan Hemorrhagic Fever is a type of viral illness known as Hantavirus Hemorrhagic Fever with Renal Syndrome. It is caused by the Dobrava-Belgrade virus, which is transmitted through contact with infected yellow-necked field mice (Apodemus flavicollis). Common symptoms of Balkan Hemorrhagic Fever include headache, fever, muscle pain, facial flush, petechiae, proteinuria, and renal failure.

Adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma (HTLV-1 positive) is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. It is caused by the human T-lymphotropic virus 1 (HTLV-1), which is transmitted through close contact, such as kissing or sharing needles. Symptoms may include fever, weight loss, night sweats, and swollen lymph nodes. Treatment options depend on the stage of the disease but may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and stem cell transplantation.

Maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It's a form of diabetes mellitus that occurs before the age of 25 and has a strong genetic component. The condition results from mutations in specific genes, primarily impacting beta-cell function and causing primary insulin secretion defects. MODY is also known as Mason-type diabetes due to its association with the Mason family.

Gamstorp Wellfart Syndrome is a condition characterized by progressive muscle weakness and atrophy, primarily affecting the lower extremities. It is often associated with sensory symptoms such as decreased sensitivity to touch or temperature in the hands and feet. The syndrome is typically inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and has synonymous names including myokymia, myotonia, and muscle wasting.

Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 4, also known as Amish brittle hair brain syndrome (ABHS), is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the TTDN1 gene. It affects several body systems including the hair, brain, and reproductive system.
Individuals with nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 4 have brittle hair that breaks easily, short stature, decreased fertility, and cognitive impairment without photosensitivity. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the condition, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).
There is no cure for nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 4, but treatment options may include hormone replacement therapy and management of symptoms such as hair breakage and cognitive impairment. Early diagnosis and intervention can help improve the quality of life for individuals with this disorder.
adult spinal muscular atrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the motor neurons.

Intermediate Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA II) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects motor neurons and leads to muscle weakness and respiratory failure. It typically develops in children between 6-12 months of age and has a short life expectancy. The condition is caused by mutations in the SMN1 or SMN2 genes, which are required for the survival of motor neurons. SMA II is also known as Childhood Onset SMA II, MUSCULAR ATROPHY, SPINAL, INFANTILE CHRONIC FORM, and SPINAL MUSCULAR ATROPHY TYPE II.

Congenital stationary night blindness is a type of physical disorder that occurs due to abnormalities in the prenatal development or birth, leading to hereditary night blindness. It is characterized by hemeralopia (a type of day blindness) and reduced visual acuity, and is caused by defective photoreceptor-to-bipolar cell signaling. The condition is genetic in nature, and has a common electroencephalogram (ERG) finding of reduced or absent b-waves, with normal a-waves. Another name for this condition is congenital essential nyctalopia.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy (EVR) is a type of retinal vascular disease that affects the blood vessels in the eye. It is characterized by the blockage of new blood vessel growth at the edges of the retina and the leakage or hemorrhage of blood vessels within the retina. Symptoms may include vision loss, floaters, and flashes of light. EVR can be inherited, which means it runs in families, and is often diagnosed in childhood. It is essential to seek medical attention if you experience any symptoms related to this condition.

Posterior polar cataract is a type of cataract characterized by a distinctive discoid lens opacity situated posteriorly and adjacent to the posterior capsule. It has the exact synonym "cataract, posterior polar."

Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1 (CMT1) is a specific subtype of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease characterized by demyelination of the peripheral nerve axons. Another name for CMT1 is Hereditary Motor and Sensory Neuropathy Type 1 (HMSN1).

Hereditary Motor and Sensory Neuropathy (HMSN) is a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth (CMT) disease that affects the peripheral nerves, specifically those responsible for motor and sensory functions. HMSN can be further classified into different types based on their genetic basis, such as Guadalajara neuronal type, Okinawa type, and others. It is important to note that while there are similarities in symptoms among these types, each type may have unique features and presentations. A diagnosis of HMSN should be made by a healthcare professional with expertise in neuromuscular disorders.

Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 3, also known as Dejerine-Sottas neuropathy or Dejerine-Sottas syndrome, is a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT) that is characterized by motor and sensory peripheral neuropathies caused by demyelination. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that it can be passed down through the genes from one generation to another. However, in some cases, it may also be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

CMT type 3 is caused by mutations in the PMP2 gene, which encodes a protein involved in myelin sheath formation around peripheral nerve fibers. These mutations can result in the production of abnormal or missing myelin sheaths, leading to demyelination and ultimately causing symptoms such as muscle weakness, sensory loss, and pain in the arms, legs, hands, and feet.

It is important to note that while Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 3 can be a debilitating condition, advances in research and treatment options are continually being made, and with proper management and care, many people with this disorder are able to lead fulfilling lives.
