Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 4 is a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease characterized by demyelinating or axonal abnormalities that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It has the exact synonym hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy. Is there anything else I can help you with?
Charcot-Marie-Tooth (CMT) disease type X is a specific subtype of CMT characterized by an X-linked inheritance pattern due to a point mutation in the connexin-32 gene.

charcot marie tooth disease intermediate type is a subtype of charcot marie tooth disease. it's characterized by motor conduction velocities above and below 38 m/s. It's also known as charcot-marie-tooth disease dominant intermediate, or charcot-marie-tooth disease recessive intermediate.

Hypermethioninemia is a medical condition that involves an excess of the amino acid methionine in the blood. This occurs when the body is unable to properly break down methionine, which can lead to an accumulation of this amino acid over time. It is important for individuals with hypermethioninemia to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their condition and ensure a balanced diet that includes appropriate levels of protein and other nutrients.

Visceral heterotaxy is a term used to describe the abnormal positioning of organs within the chest and abdomen. It occurs when the organs do not develop in their usual location, which can lead to various health issues.

Congenital adrenal insufficiency (CAI) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it can be passed down through the genes from one parent to the other. It is also possible for CAI to be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, where both parents pass on the gene for the disorder, resulting in higher risk for offspring.
CAI occurs when the adrenal gland does not produce enough cortisol or aldosterone, which are important hormones that help regulate blood pressure and respond to stress. This can lead to a variety of symptoms, including weakness, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, and low blood sugar levels.
CAI can be diagnosed through various tests, such as blood tests to measure cortisol and aldosterone levels or imaging studies like MRI or CT scan to assess the size and structure of the adrenal gland. Treatment options may include medications to replace missing hormones or surgery in some cases.
It is important for individuals with CAI to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms and ensure proper treatment. With appropriate care, those with CAI can lead a normal life.
That is correct. Familial medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) is a type of MTC that has a genetic basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is also known as thyroid carcinoma, familial medullary.

Hereditary Sensory Neuropathy (HSN) is a type of neuropathy that is characterized by congenital insensitivity to pain, which can lead to ulcerations on the fingers, tongue, lips, and other distal appendages. It is also known as Hereditary Sensory and Autonomic Neuropathy (HSAN) or familial dysautonomia, type II.

Saldino Noonan Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects various body systems, including the heart and blood vessels. It is caused by mutations in the BRAF gene, which leads to abnormal cell growth and development. People with SNS may have symptoms such as short stature, craniofacial defects, heart problems, and other health issues. Treatment options depend on the specific symptoms and complications of each case but may involve surgery or medication to manage related conditions. It is important for those affected by this disorder to receive proper care and support from a team of medical professionals.

proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the body's proteasome system. This leads to the inflammation of the body, with symptoms including joint contractures, muscular atrophy, microcytic anemia, and paniculitis-induced lipodystrophy. It is also known as CANDLE syndrome or JOINT CONTRACTURES, MUSCULAR ATROPHY, MICROCYTIC ANEMIA, AND PANNICULITIS-INDUCED LIPODYSTROPHY. It has a genetic basis and is caused by mutations in the PSMB8 gene on chromosome 6p21 or a combination of mutations in the PSMB8 gene and either the PSMA3 gene on chromosome 14q23 or the PSMB4 gene on chromosome 1q21. It is also known as Nakajo-Nishimura syndrome, proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndrome 1, and PRAAS1.

X-linked sideroblastic anemia with ataxia is a type of sideroblastic anemia that is characterized by decreased production of hemoglobin and ataxia, and has a material basis in the mutation in the ABCB7 gene. It can also be known as Anemia sideroblastic and spinocerebellar ataxia, or X-linked sideroblastic anemia with ataxia.

Congenital muscular dystrophy is a type of physical disorder that affects the muscles and causes weakness and degeneration over time. It is characterized by diminished muscle tone, progressive muscle weakness, abnormally fixed joints, spinal rigidity, and delays in reaching motor milestones such as sitting or standing unassisted. The disorder has a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth and can be inherited or occur spontaneously.

Ullrich congenital muscular dystrophy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy that affects the skeletal and cardiac muscles, and often leads to early onset respiratory failure. It is an autosomal dominant disease that has a mutation in the COL6A1, COL6A2 and COL6A3 genes which produce components of type VI collagen. It is characterized by muscle weakness and respiratory depression, and often presents in infancy or early childhood. It also has some symptoms that include delayed motor development and joint contractures. The disease has a material basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth.

Congenital muscular dystrophy, Fukuyama type (FCD) is a genetic disorder characterized by severe intellectual and developmental disability, impaired vision, cardiac abnormalities, muscle weakness, and failure to thrive. It is caused by mutations in the FKTN gene that produces the fukutin protein. FCD is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Walker-Warburg syndrome, also known as WWS, is a rare genetic disorder that affects muscle and the nervous system. It is a form of congenital muscular dystrophy, which means it is present at birth and causes muscle weakness. WWS typically causes severe intellectual and developmental disability, seizures, and early death.

WWS is caused by mutations in multiple genes, including POMT1, POMT2, ISPD, FKTN, FKRP, and LARGE1. These genes are involved in various cellular processes, such as glycosylation and detoxification of the toxic compound homocysteine.

The symptoms of WWS can vary widely among affected individuals, but common features include:
- Hypotonia (low muscle tone)
- Seizures
- Intellectual and developmental disability
- Eye abnormalities
- Short stature
- Muscle weakness
- Cataracts

WWS can also affect the liver, heart, kidney, and pancreas. Treatment often focuses on managing symptoms, preventing complications, and providing support to affected individuals and their families.

Lennox-Gastaut syndrome (LGS) is a type of epilepsy that typically begins in childhood. It is characterized by frequent seizures and intellectual disability. The exact cause of LGS is not known, but it is believed to be related to abnormal brain development or damage. Treatment options for LGS may include medications, behavioral therapies, and surgical interventions.

West syndrome, also known as infantile spasms syndrome, is a rare neurological disorder that typically affects young children. It is characterized by multiple types of seizures, including hypsarrhythmia (a pattern of abnormal brain waves on electroencephalography) and infantile spasms. In addition to these seizure types, affected individuals may also have intellectual disability or developmental delays. The exact cause of West syndrome is not well understood, but it can be associated with certain genetic mutations or other underlying medical conditions. Treatment options for West syndrome typically involve medication and/or nutritional therapy to help manage the seizures and support brain development.

nonsyndromic deafness is a type of auditory system disease that is characterized by permanent hearing loss caused by damage to structures in the inner ear and/or the middle ear, which is not associated with other signs and symptoms. This condition can be inherited or acquired through various environmental factors such as exposure to loud noises or certain medications. It is important for individuals with nonsyndromic deafness to seek medical attention and follow recommended treatments to manage their hearing loss and improve communication.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness is a type of nonsyndromic deafness, characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance mode. It has the definition A nonsyndromic deafness characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance mode. and an exact synonym Autosomal dominant deafness.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness is a type of genetic condition where the individual has a mutation in one of their copies of a specific gene, which results in a lack of ability to hear. This type of deafness is passed down through families and can affect people of all ages. It is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance mode, meaning that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, in order to develop the condition.

User, you are correct. X-linked nonsyndromic deafness is a type of nonsyndromic deafness characterized by an X-linked inheritance mode. This means that the gene responsible for this condition is located on the X chromosome and can be passed down from one generation to the next, but it usually only affects males because they have only one X chromosome (XY).
orofacial cleft is a type of physical disorder.

Spondylocostal dysostosis, also known as Jarcho-Levin syndrome, is a type of congenital disorder that affects the development of the vertebrae and ribs. It is characterized by abnormal bone growth and improper joining of the bones in the spine, resulting in a misshapen spine and other skeletal abnormalities.
It's caused by mutations in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 1 (FGFR1) gene, which plays a crucial role in the development of the skeleton. It is more commonly found in males than females and can lead to various complications if left untreated such as spinal stenosis, scoliosis and kyphosis.
Treatment options for Spondylocostal dysostosis include physical therapy, braces or other orthotic devices, medication, and surgery in severe cases. Early detection is important to ensure the best possible outcome.

Seckel syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects growth and development. It is characterized by intrauterine growth retardation, postnatal dwarfism, microcephaly, and intellectual disability. The condition has various synonyms such as Harper's syndrome, Virchow-Seckel dwarfism, bird-headed dwarfism, and microcephalic primordial dwarfism. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the disorder to develop.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation. Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I refers to a condition where there is an abnormality in the prenatal development or birth that leads to under-glycosylated serum glycoproteins.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type II, also known as alpha-dystroglycan glycoprotein ligand-1 deficiency or Oculopharyngolism Type 2, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormalities in the glycosylation of proteins. Specifically, this disorder affects the trimming and processing of protein-bound oligosaccharide chains in the brain.
Patients with CDG type II may experience symptoms such as developmental delays, intellectual disability, seizures, and vision loss. The condition is typically diagnosed during early childhood and can be inherited through autosomal recessive inheritance or spontaneous mutations.
In summary, Congenital disorder of glycosylation type II is a rare genetic disorder that affects the glycosylation of proteins, leading to various developmental and physical symptoms in affected individuals.

Cone-rod dystrophy is a type of monogenic disease that affects the retinal photoreceptors, specifically the cone and rod cells. It is characterized by progressive degeneration of these cells, leading to vision loss. The exact synonym for cone-rod dystrophy is "cone-rod retinal dystrophy."

2 Hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the excessive buildup of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the body. This leads to progressive brain damage, intellectual disability, and other health problems. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that both copies of the gene need to be mutated for the disorder to develop.

L-2-Hydroxyglutaric aciduria, also known as L-2-hydroxyglutaric acidemia, is a rare metabolic disorder that affects the cerebellum. It occurs when there is an accumulation of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the body, which damages the cerebellum and can lead to problems with movement coordination, balance, and muscle coordination (ataxia). The disorder has a genetic basis, and it is typically inherited from one's parents. There are different types of L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria, including hereditary and non-hereditary forms, but they all share the common characteristic of cerebellar damage. The disorder can be diagnosed through a combination of medical history, physical examination, laboratory tests, and imaging studies such as MRI or CT scan. Treatment options may include enzyme replacement therapy, dietary restrictions, and supportive care to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

D 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the buildup of the compound D-2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the body. This accumulation can lead to various symptoms, including developmental delay, seizures, and weak muscle tone (hypotonia). Additionally, this condition affects the cerebrum, which is the largest part of the brain and responsible for controlling important functions such as muscle movement, speech, vision, thinking, emotion, and memory.

Senior Loken Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by progressive wasting of the filtering unit of the kidney (nephronophthisis), with or without medullary cystic renal disease, and progressive eye disease. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that it is inherited from both parents and can affect any one of their offspring regardless of gender. The syndrome was first described by Loken in 1962 and has since been named after him. Some synonyms for Senior Loken Syndrome include renal-retinal syndrome and Loken Senior syndrome.

Cranioectodermal dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the premature fusion of the cranial sutures, which leads to abnormal skull development and various ectodermal, endodermal, and mesodermal defects. It is also known as Levin syndrome or Sensenbrenner syndrome.
Occult macular dystrophy is a type of macular degeneration characterized by central cone dysfunction leading to vision loss with normal fundus and fluorescein angiography findings.

Glycogen storage disease XV is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by muscle weakness and cardiac abnormalities. The condition is caused by mutations in the GYG1 gene, which encodes glycogenin-1. This disease has exact synonyms including "Glycogen storage disease 15," "Glycogen storage disease with severe cardiomyopathy due to glycogenin deficiency," and "glycogen storage disease type XV."

Hereditary lymphedema, also known as primary lymphedema, is a type of lymphedema that is caused by an inherited genetic defect in the lymphatic system. It most commonly affects the legs and can cause swelling due to impaired lymph flow and accumulation of lymph fluid. The condition typically presents at birth or during early childhood, although it can also develop later in life.

Brachydactyly is a term used to describe a condition where one or more of the digits (fingers and/
toes) are significantly shorter than average. It is classified as a type of dysostosis, which refers to abnormal bone growth or development. The exact cause of brachydactyly is not always clear, but it can be genetic in nature, meaning that it may be passed down through families. In some cases, brachydactyly may also be the result of certain medical conditions or injuries. It is important to note that brachydactyly does not typically cause any significant pain or discomfort, and most people with this condition lead normal lives. However, in some cases, it may require specialized treatment or surgery to correct any functional issues related to the shortened digits.

Gummatous syphilis is a type of tertiary syphilis that is characterized by granulomatous lesions, called gummas, which are characterized by a center of necrotic tissue with a rubbery texture. They form in the liver, bones, and testes but may affect any organ.

Congenital generalized lipodystrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease where there is extreme scarcity of subcutaneous fat, muscular hypertrophy, fatty liver, hypertriglyceridemia and metabolic complications including insulin resistance.

Trichotillomania is a disorder characterized by the repetitive plucking of one's hair, often leading to significant hair loss. It is classified as an impulse control disorder due to its similarities with other conditions such as obsessive-compulsive disorder and substance use disorders. People who suffer from trichotillomania may experience feelings of stress or anxiety that prompt them to pluck their hair, and they may also have a hard time stopping this behavior despite the negative consequences. In some cases, trichotillomania can lead to significant hair loss and even scarring. It is important for individuals who struggle with this disorder to seek professional help and support to manage their symptoms effectively.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B1 is a genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness and cognitive impairment. It is caused by mutations in the POMT1 gene, which encodes O-mannosyltransferase. This condition has been described as congenital muscular dystrophy with impaired intellectual development B1.

That is correct. Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) is a term used to describe two chronic inflammatory conditions of the gastrointestinal tract: Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis. Both conditions can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract, from the mouth to the anus, and can cause a range of symptoms, including abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, rectal bleeding, and fever. IBD is believed to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors, and it can lead to complications such as malnutrition, weight loss, and increased risk of cancer. Treatment for IBD typically involves a combination of medications, dietary changes, and, in some cases, surgery.

Severe congenital neutropenia is a type of physical disorder that results from an abnormality in prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by a maturation arrest of granulopoiesis at the level of promyelocytes and early onset of severe bacterial infections.

Tooth agenesis is a type of tooth disease characterized by the failure to develop one or more missing teeth. It is also referred to as familial tooth agenesis, hypodontia, oligodontia, and selective tooth agenesis.

Asphyxiating Thoracic Dystrophy, also known as Jeune Syndrome, is a bone development disorder characterized by skeletal abnormalities and difficulty breathing. It is caused by mutations in the Cilia genes, resulting in ciliopathy. This condition can lead to short-rib thoracic dysplasia with or without polydactyly, as well as thoracic pelvic phalangeal dystrophy.
Primary congenital glaucoma is a type of monogenic disease.

Glycogen storage disease IX, also known as GSD9, is a type of glycogen storage disease characterized by deficiency in hepatic phosphorylase kinase activity. It is one of the rarest forms of GSD and can lead to various symptoms depending on the severity of the condition.

Taeniasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that has material basis in either Taenia solium or Taenia saginata. These species are transmitted by ingestion of undercooked contaminated meat. It can also be referred to as Beef tapeworm infection, Infection by Taeniarhynchus saginatus, or Taenia saginata infectious disease.

Intestinal schistosomiasis is a type of parasitic infection that affects the intestines, caused by the Schistosoma species of flatworms. Symptoms can include fever, cough, abdominal pain, diarrhea, hepatosplenomegaly, bloody stools, and eosinophilia. It is also known as Katayama fever or Schistosoma japonicum infection.
extrapulmonary tuberculosis is a term used to describe cases of tuberculosis outside the lungs.

Abdominal tuberculosis is a type of extrapulmonary tuberculosis that occurs when the bacteria that cause TB spread to other parts of the body, including the gastrointestinal tract, peritoneum, omentum, mesentery, liver, spleen, and pancreas.

AbCD Syndrome, also known as Oculocutaneous Albinism with Neurological Disorders and Deafness, is a rare genetic disorder that results from mutations in the EDNRB gene. It primarily affects the skin, hair, eyes, and inner ear, causing light-skinned or white-haired individuals, poor visual acuity, and hearing impairments.

AbCD Syndrome is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It can also cause cell migration disorders in the brain and spine, as well as neurocyte migration disorders in the gastrointestinal tract.

In summary, AbCD Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by albinism, black lock, cell migration disorder of the neurocytes of the gut, and sensorineural deafness, which are caused by mutations in the EDNRB gene.

Adult-onset diabetes and adult-onset polycystic ovary syndrome are types of adult-onset diseases.

adult-onset disease has exact synonym adult-type diabetes.
Adult-onset polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is also known as Stein-Leventhal syndrome.

Triple A Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the autonomic nervous system. It is characterized by achalasia, adrenal insufficiency and alacrima. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the AAAS gene which encodes for ALADIN, a protein located within the nuclear envelope. These mutations result in dysfunction of the autonomic nervous system. It is also known as Achalasia-Addisonianism-Alacrimia Syndrome and Allgrove Syndrome.

Achieiropodia, also known as Achieiropodia or Acheiropodia, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the absence or underdevelopment of the distal extremities. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the LMBR1 gene and is considered to be a form of osteochondrodysplasia. It is also sometimes referred to as Horn-Kolb Syndrome, although this term is not as widely used. There is no cure for Achieiropodia, but treatment may include physical therapy, braces, or other assistive devices to help manage the symptoms and improve mobility.

Acrocapitofemoral dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by skeletal dysplasia, brachydactyly (abnormally shortened fingers and toes), and a narrow thorax. It has a material basis in mutations in the Indian hedgehog homolog gene.

Acrodermatitis enteropathica is a disorder that affects the skin and hair of a person. It occurs due to a metabolic problem involving the body's ability to absorb zinc from its diet. This condition causes inflammation in the skin around the mouth, nose, anus, and fingers and toes. Additionally, it can cause diarrhea, weight loss, and hair loss. The disorder is caused by a mutation in the SLC39A4 gene, which encodes a protein responsible for zinc absorption in the small intestine.

acrokeratosis verruciformis is a skin condition characterized by thickened, rough, and scaly skin. It is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by mutations in the ATP2A2 gene. The condition has been named after dermatologist Hans Hopf, who first described it in 1923. Acrokeratosis verruciformis of Hopf is another name for this skin condition.

An Askin's tumor is a type of Ewing sarcoma that arises from the soft tissues of the chest wall and tends to recur locally, rather than widely disseminating. It can also be referred to as an Askin tumor or Askin's tumour.

oral cavity carcinoma in situ (also known as oral cancer) is a type of mouth disease characterized by abnormal cell growth in the lining of the mouth. It occurs when healthy cells in the mouth are replaced with cancerous cells, which can form tumors and spread to other areas of the body if left untreated. In situ carcinoma refers to cancer that has developed within an organ but has not yet spread beyond it. In this case, oral cavity carcinoma in situ specifically affects the mouth and is located in the epithelium (the lining) of the oral cavity. It is often associated with leukoplakia, which is a white patch or plaque on the tongue that can be a sign of oral cancer. If caught early enough, it can be treated with surgery to remove the affected cells and prevent further spread of the disease.

Pharyngeal carcinoma in situ, also known as Ossified Fibrous Dysplasia (OFD), is a condition in which malignant cells are present but have not yet invaded surrounding tissues. It is considered to be the earliest stage of pharyngeal cancer and has a high risk of developing into more advanced stages if left untreated. OFD usually affects young adults and can lead to the loss of function in the throat, difficulty swallowing, and even death if not treated promptly. Treatment options for OFD may include surgery, radiation therapy, or a combination of both. Early diagnosis is crucial to ensure the best possible outcome.

Gallbladder carcinoma in situ, also known as gallbladder cancer, is a type of cancer that affects the surface epithelium of the gallbladder. It is a precancerous condition where abnormal cells have begun to grow and multiply but have not yet spread to other parts of the body. This condition is more common in women than men and often occurs after the age of 65.
Gallbladder carcinoma in situ can be treated through surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy. Early detection and treatment are crucial for increasing the chances of a successful recovery. If you suspect that you may have gallbladder cancer, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional for further evaluation and treatment options.

Bile duct carcinoma in situ, also known as intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasia (IPMN), is a type of bile duct disease. It refers to the abnormal growth of cells within the bile ducts that can lead to cancer if left untreated. This condition is considered in situ because it remains confined to the walls of the bile duct, rather than spreading to other parts of the body.

IPMN is a type of in situ carcinoma, which means it starts as a non-invasive cancer that has not yet invaded surrounding tissues or organs. It is typically found through imaging tests such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI. In some cases, it may be diagnosed during a procedure called endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), which allows doctors to examine the bile ducts and pancreas using a flexible camera.

Treatment for IPMN usually involves surgery to remove the affected portion of the bile duct, as well as any lymph nodes that may be involved. The type of surgery depends on the location and extent of the disease, but may include a partial hepatectomy (removal of part of the liver), a cholecystectomy (removal of the gallbladder), or a bile duct excision (surgical removal of the affected bile duct segment).

It is important to note that IPMN can sometimes be misdiagnosed as something else, such as benign bile duct disease or other forms of cancer. Therefore, it is crucial for patients and their doctors to work closely together to determine an accurate diagnosis and develop a proper treatment plan based on the individual case.

Bronchus carcinoma in situ, also known as bronchial intraepithelial neoplasia (Bien), is a precancerous condition that occurs when abnormal cells grow inside the lining of the bronchi. These abnormal cells can become cancerous over time if left untreated. Bronchus carcinoma in situ is a type of in situ carcinoma, which means it starts in the innermost layer of tissue and has the potential to progress to invasive cancer if left untreated.

Bronchus carcinoma in situ most commonly develops into adenocarcinoma, a type of lung cancer that originates from glandular cells found within the bronchioles. It is important to note that not all cases of bronchus carcinoma in situ progress to invasive cancer, but early detection and treatment are crucial to minimize the risk of progression.

In summary, bronchus carcinoma in situ is a precancerous condition that occurs when abnormal cells grow inside the lining of the bronchi. It has the potential to progress to invasive cancer if left untreated, and early detection and treatment are essential to minimize the risk of progression.

respiratory system cancer refers to the growth of abnormal cells within the respiratory system. This can include various types of cancer that affect the lungs, airways, or other parts of the respiratory system. These cancers are characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation in the respiratory tract and may cause a range of symptoms depending on which part of the respiratory system is affected. Respiratory system cancer is considered an organ system cancer, as it affects a specific organ within the body.

Paranasal sinus cancer is a type of cancer that occurs in the paranasal sinuses, which are located near the nasal passages. It is considered a respiratory system cancer because it affects the airways in the face and head. Paranasal sinus cancer can be further classified as Epidermoid carcinoma of the paranasal sinus, Mucoepidermoid carcinoma of Accessory sinus, adenoid cystic carcinoma of Accessory sinus, paranasal sinus adenocarcinoma, paranasal sinus adenoid cystic carcinoma, paranasal sinus mucoepidermoid carcinoma, or paranasal sinus squamous cell carcinoma. It is important to note that these terms are sometimes used interchangeably and may have slightly different meanings in certain contexts.

Infiltrating renal pelvis transitional cell carcinoma is a type of renal pelvis transitional cell carcinoma that has grown into and through the walls of the renal pelvis. It originates in the transitional epithelium of the renal pelvis, which is the area where the ureter and bladder merge with the kidney. This type of cancer can be aggressive and may spread quickly to other parts of the body if not detected early and treated properly.

respiratory system benign neoplasm is a type of organ growth that develops in the respiratory system and is considered to be non-cancerous. These tumors are typically slow-growing and do not spread to other parts of the body as aggressively as malignant (cancerous) tumors. Respiratory system benign neoplasms can affect various components of the respiratory system, such as the nasal sinuses, trachea, bronchi, or lung tissue. It is important to note that while these tumors do not spread as quickly as malignant tumors, they may still cause significant problems if left untreated due to their size and location within the respiratory system.

Reproductive organ benign neoplasm refers to the growth of abnormal cells in the reproductive organs, such as the ovaries or testes. These abnormal cell growths are also known as benign neoplasms, which means they do not spread to other parts of the body like cancer can. However, if left untreated, some types of benign neoplasms may cause problems due to their size and pressure on surrounding tissues or organs. While it is a non-cancerous growth, it's essential to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Bladder benign neoplasm refers to a type of urinary system benign neoplasm that occurs in the bladder, typically affecting the urothelial cells lining the bladder. Bladder benign neoplasms can include various types of tumors such as papillomas, leiomyomas, fibromas, hemangiomas, neurofibromas, and lipomas. These tumors are generally non-cancerous but may cause symptoms like urinary problems or discomfort due to their size or location. Bladder benign neoplasms are different from bladder cancer, which is a malignant growth in the urinary system.

Gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm is a type of organ growth that occurs in the gastrointestinal tract and is typically non-cancerous. It can include conditions such as polyps, which are abnormal growths of tissue in the gastrointestinal tract. These types of benign neoplasms are generally not life-threatening but may require treatment to prevent complications such as bleeding or obstruction.

Biliary tract benign neoplasm refers to a type of non-cancerous growth or tumor that occurs in the biliary tree, which is the network of ducts that transport bile from the liver to the gallbladder and then to the small intestine. This type of neoplasm can affect both the liver and the extrahepatic bile ducts, which are the ducts that carry bile outside the liver. Biliary tract benign neoplasm is a type of hepatobiliary benign neoplasm, which refers to non-cancerous growths that occur in the liver, gallbladder, or extrahepatic bile ducts.

Gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumor (GINET) is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer that originates from neuroendocrine cells. It has the exact synonyms of gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumour (GINT) and malignant gastrointestinal neuroendocrine tumor (MGINET).

Advanced sleep phase syndrome, also known as familial advanced sleep-phase syndrome (FASPS), is a type of sleep disorder characterized by an altered circadian rhythm that causes individuals to fall asleep in the early evening and wake up very early in the morning. It is believed to have a genetic component, with some studies suggesting it may be linked to autosomal dominant inheritance. However, more research is needed to fully understand the underlying mechanisms and genetics of this sleep disorder.

Aicardi-Goutieres Syndrome (AGS) is a genetic disorder that affects the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by cerebral atrophy, leukodystrophy, intracranial calcifications, chronic cerebrospinal fluid lymphocytosis, increased CSF alpha-interferon, and negative serologic investigations for common prenatal infections. It is a type of autosomal genetic disease that has a material basis in some forms of inheritance. The exact synonyms for AGS are Aicardi Syndrome and Cree Encephalitis.

Aland Island eye disease, also known as Forsius-Eriksson Syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the eyes. It is a type of X-linked recessive eye disease, which means it is passed down through generations by males and can cause severe vision loss in affected individuals.

The disease is characterized by fundus hypopigmentation (lack of pigmentation in the retina), decreased visual acuity (difficulty seeing fine details), nystagmus (involuntary eye movements), astigmatism, myopia (nearsightedness), and defective darkness adaptation. It has a material basis in mutations in the CACNA1F gene, which provides instructions for making a protein that is essential for proper functioning of the eyes.

Overall, Aland Island eye disease can significantly impact an individual's quality of life due to its impact on vision. However, with early detection and appropriate medical care, it can be managed effectively.

Allan Herndon Dudley Syndrome (AHDS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the brain development in infants and children. It's caused by mutations in the SLC16A2 gene, which encodes for the monocarboxylate transporter-8 protein (MCT8). This protein is responsible for transporting the thyroid hormone T3 into nerve cells of the developing brain, but when it's not functioning properly due to the mutation, it can cause intellectual disability and other movement problems. AHDS has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, which means that the gene responsible for the condition is located on the X chromosome and generally leads to milder symptoms in males than in females because they have one functional copy of the gene.
oculocutaneous albinism is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

ocular albinism 1 is a genetic condition that affects the eyes and causes vision problems. It is characterized by reduced pigmentation of the iris, which can make it difficult to see in bright sunlight. The condition also has an impact on the color of the hair and skin, but not as severely as other forms of albinism. Ocular albinism 1 is caused by a mutation in the GPR143 gene, which codes for segments of the melanosomes that store melanin. It can be inherited from one or both parents and may affect people of all ages and ethnic backgrounds. While there is no cure for ocular albinism 1, early detection and appropriate treatment can help manage its symptoms and improve quality of life.

Alopecia Universalis is a medical condition characterized by the complete loss of hair on the scalp and body. It is an autosomal recessive genetic disorder, which means that it is passed down through generations by inheritance from both parents. The condition can affect individuals of any age, but it usually begins in childhood or adolescence. It's important to note that Alopecia Universalis is different from common hair loss conditions like Telogen Effluvium and Androgenic Alopecia.

transthyretin amyloidosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the buildup of abnormal protein deposits in various organs and tissues, leading to multiple organ dysfunction. It can also cause cardiomyopathy, nephropathy, vitreous opacities, and CNS amyloidosis. The condition has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the TTR gene being the primary cause of inheritance.

Primary cutaneous amyloidosis is a type of skin disease that is characterized by the buildup of abnormal proteins called amyloid in the skin. It can also affect the nails and other parts of the body. It is often inherited, and there are different types based on where the amyloid is deposited in the body. The exact synonyms for primary cutaneous amyloidosis include familial primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis. It can cause symptoms such as itching, skin scratching, and deposits of amyloid in the dermis.

Anauxetic dysplasia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by abnormal development of the spine and long bones. It is caused by mutations in the RMRP gene, which is located on chromosome 9p13. The condition can lead to short stature, bone deformities, and other health problems. It is also sometimes referred to as spondylometaepiphyseal dysplasia, Menger type.

Rh deficiency syndrome is a type of hemolytic anemia that occurs due to the lack of Rh antigens on red blood cells. This condition can be caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RHAG gene, which is located on chromosome 6p12.
Hypochromic microcytic anemia is a type of microcytic anemia characterized by paler than normal blood cells.

arterial calcification of infancy is a condition where the arteries in infants become narrow and hard due to the buildup of calcium.
arterial calcification of infancy is a condition that at least disease has location some infantile onset.
arterial calcification of infancy is a type of vascular disease characterized by the stiffening, narrowing, or hardening of the arteries due to an excessive buildup of calcium in their walls.
arterial calcification of infancy has definition A vascular disease that is characterized by generalized calcification of the arterial internal elastic lamina, leading to rupture of the lamina and occlusive changes in the tunica intima with stenosis and decreased elasticity of the vessel wall.
arterial calcification of infancy has exact synonym generalized arterial calcification of infancy.
arterial calcification of infancy has exact synonym idiopathic infantile arterial calcification.
arterial calcification of infancy has exact synonym infantile arteriosclerosis.
arterial tortuosity syndrome is a condition characterized by the elongation and generalized tortuosity of the major arteries, including the aorta. It's considered a type of connective tissue disease.

Distal Arthrogryposis is a type of muscle disorder that affects the joints and muscles in the hands and feet. It is characterized by congenital contractures, which are fixed deformities in the joints caused by abnormal fibrosis of the connective tissue surrounding the muscles. This can lead to limited mobility and deformity in the affected limbs. The condition is usually diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can be inherited in some cases. There is no cure for Distal Arthrogryposis, but treatment may include physical therapy, splints, and other interventions to help improve mobility and alleviate pain.

arts syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of children. it is characterized by profound congenital sensorineural hearing impairment, early-onset hypotonia, delayed motor development, mild to moderate intellectual disability, ataxia, and an increased risk of infections. it has a mutation in the PRPS1 gene which is located on the x chromosome. It can cause severe health problems and can be fatal if not treated properly. It has also been known as Lethal ataxia with deafness and optic atrophy, MRXS18, syndromic X-linked mental retardation 18, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Arts type.

Atelosteogenesis is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of long bones in newborns, resulting in abnormal growth and short stature. It is one of several types of osteochondrodysplasias, which are characterized by abnormal development or growth of cartilage and bone. Atelosteogenesis specifically affects the humeri (upper arms), femora (thighbones), and spine, leading to unique patterns of aplasia/hypoplasia in these areas. The disorder is caused by mutations in one of several genes involved in cartilage development, and it can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that both copies of the gene must be mutated for the disorder to be expressed.

atransferrinemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the transferrin gene. It causes microcytic anemia, iron overload and has a material basis in inheritance from two copies of mutated genes or one copy of each of two different mutated genes. Familial hypotransferrinemia is another name for this condition.

Familial atrial fibrillation is a specific type of atrial fibrillation that has a genetic basis and can be passed down through families. It is characterized by an irregular heartbeat, which can lead to an increased risk of stroke, heart failure, and other complications. Treatment may include medications, lifestyle changes, or procedures such as ablation or pacemaker implantation.

atrioventricular septal defect is a congenital heart defect that occurs when the superior and inferior endocardial cushions of the heart do not fuse properly with the mid portion of the atrial septum and the muscular portion of the ventricular septum. This results in an abnormal or inadequate closure of the foramen ovale, which allows extra blood to flow into the lungs. The condition is also known as AVCD, AVSD, ECD, atrioventricular canal defect, and endocardial cushion defect.

Baller-Gerold Syndrome is indeed a rare condition that affects the skull and skeletal system. It is characterized by coronal craniosynostosis, which is the premature fusion of several bones in the skull, resulting in an abnormally shaped head. This syndrome can also cause short stature (due to the effect on growth) and aplasia or hypoplasia of the radial bone (a condition where one or both of the bones that form the forearm are underdeveloped).
If you have any further questions about Baller-Gerold Syndrome, feel free to ask!

The Bamforth-Lazarus syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by hypothyroidism, cleft palate, spiky hair, and bifid epiglottis. It is caused by a homozygous mutation in the FKHL15 gene on chromosome 9q22. The exact synonym for this condition is hypothyroidism, athyral with spiky hair and cleft palate.

Pseudo torch syndrome 1 is a rare genetic disorder that affects brain development. It causes microcephaly, which is a condition where the head is smaller than average, and other serious problems such as intracranial calcifications, intellectual disability, simplified gyration, and polymicrogyria. These issues are caused by mutations in the OCLN gene on chromosome 5q13.2. The disorder has been described under several different names including BLC-PMG, Baraitser-Brett-Piesowicz syndrome, Baraitser-Reardon syndrome, PTORCH1, band-like calcification with simplified gyration and polymicrogyria, bilateral band-like calcification with polymicrogyria, microcephaly-intracranial calcification-intellectual disability syndrome.

Bannayan-Riley-Ruvalcaba syndrome (BRRS) is a rare autosomal dominant genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems. It is characterized by macrocephaly, multiple hamartomas (benign tumors), and dark freckles on the face, neck, and trunk. The disorder has been associated with germline mutations in the PTEN gene located on chromosome 10q23.

BRRS is considered to be a part of Cowden syndrome, which is also known as Bannayan-Zonana syndrome. However, it should not be confused with Bannayan-Zonana syndrome, which is a distinct disorder with similar features but has different genetic causes.

BRRS can affect various organs such as the brain, kidneys, liver, and gastrointestinal system. It may also result in developmental delays, growth problems, and an increased risk of certain types of cancer. The symptoms of BRRS may vary greatly among affected individuals and can range from mild to severe.

Early diagnosis and proper management are crucial for individuals with BRRS to minimize the risk of complications and ensure the best possible outcome. Treatment options may include surgery, medications, or other interventions as needed based on the specific symptoms and organ systems involved.

Bart Pumphrey Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin, hair, and hearing. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The syndrome is characterized by leukonychia, wart-like skin growths, palmoplantar keratoderma, and hearing loss. It is caused by a mutation in the GJB2 gene on chromosome 13q12. There is no cure for this disorder, but early diagnosis can help manage symptoms.

Biotin-responsive basal ganglia disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the brain and can cause symptoms such as ataxia, confusion, seizures, dysphagia, dystonia, and other problems. It is caused by a deficiency of biotin, which is an essential nutrient for the proper functioning of the basal ganglia. Treatment typically involves supplements to increase biotin levels in the body.

Beare-Stevenson cutis gyrata syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disorder that is characterized by the presence of cutis gyrata, acanthosis nigricans, and craniosynostosis. It is caused by mutations in the FGFR2 gene located on chromosome 10q26.

vitelliform macular dystrophy is a form of age-related macular degeneration that affects the macula, which is responsible for sharp central vision. It is characterized by the disruption of cells in a small area near the center of the retina and can cause progressive vision loss over time. The condition is also known as Best disease, juvenile-onset vitelliform macular dystrophy, or Best macular dystrophy.

Bestrophinopathy is a type of macular degeneration that affects the retina and causes central vision loss. It is caused by mutations in the BEST1 gene on chromosome 11q12, which results in an absent electrooculogram light rise and reduced electroretinogram. Bestrophinopathy has a strong autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, meaning that it is passed down through generations by individuals who have a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BEST1 gene.

Bethlem myopathy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy that is characterized by progressive myopathy and joint contractures. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation in the COL6A1, COL6A2, or COL6A3 genes. The condition has exact synonyms of benign congenital muscular dystrophy.

Bietti's crystalline dystrophy is a type of retinal degeneration characterized by the accumulation of crystals in the cornea, shiny deposits on the retina, and progressive atrophy of the retina, choriocapillaris, and choroid. It is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CYP4V2 gene on chromosome 4q35. The condition has an exact synonym of bietti crystalline corneoretinal dystrophy.

Fetal alcohol syndrome is a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder, which refers to a group of conditions that can occur in a child whose mother consumed alcohol during pregnancy. These disorders are characterized by physical and neurological abnormalities that can lead to a range of developmental problems. FASDs can be diagnosed prenatally or postnatally, depending on the severity of symptoms and available diagnostic tools.
The term "fetal alcohol syndrome" is used to describe a specific subtype of FASDs that includes the most severe physical and developmental abnormalities. The key features of FAS include craniofacial dysmorphology (such as microcephaly, smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, small eye openings), pre- and postnatal growth deficiency, and central nervous system dysfunction.
It is important to note that not all individuals with FAS will have all of these features, and the severity of symptoms can vary widely among affected individuals. Additionally, FASDs can have a wide range of effects on cognitive functioning, behavior, and socio-emotional development. Early intervention and support can help to mitigate the impact of these disorders on an individual's life outcomes.

Fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS) is a spectrum disorder that refers to the range of physical, behavioral, and cognitive problems that can occur in an individual whose mother consumed alcohol during pregnancy. Partial Fetal Alcohol Syndrome (pFAS) is a specific type of FAS that has some, but not all, of the characteristic features of full FAS. Specifically, pFAS includes prenatal alcohol exposure that results in growth deficiency and/or craniofacial abnormalities and central nervous system dysfunction. The diagnosis of pFAS requires a combination of physical, behavioral, and cognitive findings, along with documentation of prenatal alcohol exposure.

Alcohol-related Neurodevelopmental Disorder (ARND) is a type of Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD) that results in central nervous system dysfunction and behavioral or cognitive deficits due to prenatal alcohol exposure. It has the same definition as FASD but with a different name, which can make it easier for people to understand. ARND is also known by its exact synonyms: Static Encephalopathy, which means "brain damage" that does not get better over time.

Alcohol-related birth defects (ARBD) are a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder, which occurs when the mother drinks alcohol during pregnancy. ARBD can cause damage to various organs, bones, and muscles in the developing fetus. It is important for pregnant women to avoid consuming alcohol to prevent potential complications for their unborn child.

Spastic cerebral palsy is a form of cerebral palsy that affects the muscles, causing them to be stiff and inflexible. It occurs when there is damage to the brain's outer layer (cerebral cortex), which results in increased tone or tension in the affected muscles, leading to abnormal movements.

Cerebral palsy is a neurological disorder that affects movement and posture. There are various types of cerebral palsy, including ataxic cerebral palsy, which is caused by damage to the cerebellum, and hypoxic-ischemic cerebral palsy, which is caused by a lack of oxygen and blood flow to the brain during birth. Ataxic cerebral palsy affects muscle coordination, particularly in the limbs, and may also cause hypotonia, tremors, difficulty with visual and/or auditory processing. Hypoxic-ischemic cerebral palsy can cause a range of symptoms, including motor and sensory impairments, seizures, and developmental delays.

Female breast cancer is a type of breast cancer that develops from the breast tissue in females. It is characterized by the uncontrolled growth of cells in the breast, and can spread to other parts of the body if not treated in time. The risk factors for developing female breast cancer include age, family history, genetic predisposition, and lifestyle factors such as obesity and lack of physical activity. Early detection and regular screening are important for reducing the risk of developing breast cancer and ensuring that it can be treated effectively if it does occur.

dyskinetic cerebral palsy is a type of cerebral palsy that is characterized by a lack of muscle tone (hypotonia) and involuntary motions. It is caused by damage to the extrapyramidal motor system, which includes the basal ganglia and the pyramidal tract. This leads to difficulties in maintaining an upright, steady position for sitting or walking, and it can also affect the individual's ability to control their movements.

Mixed cerebral palsy is a type of cerebral palsy that affects the muscles and movements in the body. It occurs when there is damage to both the pyramidal and extrapyramidal areas of the brain, leading to problems with tone, coordination, balance, and posture. People with mixed cerebral palsy may have difficulty speaking, swallowing, or controlling their limbs.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect is a type of physical disorder, characterized by an abnormal conversion of cholesterol into bile acids, which occurs primarily in the liver. It has several exact synonyms, including 3-beta-hydroxy-delta-5-C27-steroid oxidoreductase deficiency, CBA (cholestasis with delta(4)-3-oxosteroid-5-beta-reductase deficiency), and cholestasis with delta(4)-3-oxosteroid-5-beta-reductase deficiency.

Birk Barel Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by intellectual disability, hypotonia (low muscle tone), hyperactivity, and facial dysmorphism. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the KCNK9 gene on chromosome 8q24. The syndrome is also known as Birk-Barel mental retardation dysmorphism syndrome.

Birt-Hogg syndrome (BHS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin, lungs, and kidneys. It is characterized by the presence of hair follicle hamartomas, which are benign tumors that arise from the hair follicles. BHS can also cause spontaneous pneumothorax (collapsed lung) and renal cell carcinoma (kidney cancer). The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the faulty gene is enough to increase the risk of developing the disorder. BHS is caused by a mutation in the FLCN gene, which is located on chromosome 17p11.2.

Bjornstad syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by early onset of hearing loss and hair loss due to pili torti. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BCS1L gene on chromosome 2q35. It also has synonyms such as BJS, PTD, and deafness-pili torti-hypogonadism syndrome.

Blau Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the joints, skin, and eyes. It is characterized by familial granulomatous arthritis, uveitis (inflammation of the eye), and skin granulomas. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the NOD2 gene. Blau Syndrome can also be referred to as Arthrocutaneouveal Granulomatosis, Jabs Syndrome, or BLAUS.

Blue cone monochromacy is a condition characterized by the absence of functional long wavelength-sensitive and medium wavelength-sensitive cones in the retina, resulting in severely impaired color discrimination, low visual acuity, nystagmus, and photophobia. It is caused by a recessive X-linked genetic disorder, which means that the condition is inherited through the X chromosome and can affect males and females differently. Males with this condition have only one working copy of the gene, while females need to have two non-working copies (one on each X chromosome) for the condition to be expressed.

Boomerang dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by severe dwarfism, dislocated joints, club feet, a distinctive facies, and dysplastic tubular bones with bowing that resembles the shape of a boomerang. It has a genetic basis, specifically due to heterozygous mutations in the FLNB gene located on chromosome 3p14.

Borjeson-Forssman-Lehmann syndrome (BFLS) is a type of X-linked recessive intellectual disability that is characterized by intellectual disability, truncal obesity, seizures, hypogonadism, developmental delay, distinctive facial features, tapered fingers and short toes. It has material basis in mutations in the PHF6 gene and has been synonymously referred to as BFLS, Borjeson syndrome, intellectual deficiency-epilepsy-endocrine disorders syndrome, mental retardation, epilepsy, and endocrine disorder, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation BFL type.

Athabaskan Brainstem Dysgenesis Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the brainstem. It is caused by mutations in the HOXA1 gene, which encodes a transcription factor important for embryonic development. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and typically presents in early childhood with symptoms such as cerebral palsy, hearing loss, and vision problems. It has been described as having a material basis in homozygous mutations in the HOXA1 gene. There is also a similar disorder known as Navajo Brainstem Syndrome.

Bothnia retinal dystrophy is a type of fundus dystrophy, characterized by early onset of night blindness and decreased visual acuity that progresses to blindness in early adulthood. It has a material basis in mutations in the RLBP1 gene. It has an exact synonym of Vasterbotten dystrophy.

Bowen-Conradi Hutterite Syndrome (BCHS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects infants, and is characterized by growth delays, failure to thrive, and malformations of the head and face. It leads to infantile death. The disorder has a homozygous mutation in the EMG1 gene on chromosome 12p13.

Small cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the lungs. It is characterized by the presence of small, round cells in the lung tissue. These cells are abnormal and do not function properly. Small cell carcinoma can also occur in other parts of the body but it is most commonly found in the lungs. It is important to note that small cell carcinoma is different from non-small cell carcinoma, which affects the larger airways in the lung. If you have been diagnosed with small cell carcinoma, it is important to seek medical attention and follow your doctor's treatment recommendations.

Organ system cancer refers to a type of cancer that originates in a specific organ or body system, such as the lung, breast, or colon. It is classified based on the organ or tissue where the cancer cells begin to grow and spread.

There are several types of organ system cancers, including:

1. Lung cancer - starts in the lungs and can affect both smokers and non-smokers.
2. Breast cancer - starts in the breast tissue and is more common in women than men.
3. Colon cancer - starts in the colon (large intestine) and can be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors.
4. Prostate cancer - starts in the prostate gland and is more common in older men.
5. Pancreatic cancer - starts in the pancreas and can affect both men and women, but is more common in men.
6. Skin cancer - starts in the skin cells and is caused by exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from sunlight or tanning beds.
7. Brain cancer - starts in the brain and can be caused by a variety of factors, such as genetic mutations, tumors, or exposure to radiation.

It's important to note that not all organ system cancers are alike, and each type has its own unique set of symptoms, causes, and treatments. If you have any concerns about your health, it's always best to consult with a medical professional for personalized advice and guidance.

It seems like you're asking about the relationship between cell types and cancer. Cancer can be classified based on the type of cells involved, which is often determined by their appearance under a microscope. For example, leukemia is a type of cancer that affects blood cells, while breast cancer is a type of cancer that originates in the breast tissue.

There are many different types of cellular cancers, each with unique features and treatments. Some common examples include:

* Carcinomas: These cancers begin in the skin or in internal organs, such as the liver, colon, or lung.
* Sarcomas: These cancers start in connective tissue, such as bone, muscle, or cartilage.
* Leukemias and lymphomas: These cancers affect the blood-forming cells in the bone marrow or the immune system's lymphatic cells.

It's important to note that not all cancers are classified by cell type. Some cancers, such as those involving the nervous system, are not necessarily classified by cell type. Additionally, some tumors may not have a clear cellular classification, and researchers may use other methods to identify them.

In summary, cancer is classified based on the type of cells involved, which can be further defined by their appearance under a microscope. There are many different types of cellular cancers, each with unique features and treatments.

Anal canal cancer, also known as rectal cancer, is a type of large intestine cancer that originates in the last several centimeters of the large intestine. It is characterized by abnormal cell growth and can spread to other parts of the body if not detected early and treated properly. The exact cause of anal canal cancer is not fully understood, but it may be linked to certain risk factors such as age, lifestyle habits, and genetic predisposition. Symptoms of anal canal cancer may include rectal bleeding, abnormal bowel movements, pain or pressure in the rectal area, and swelling or lumps in the anus. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of physical examination, digital rectal examination (DRE), anoscopy, sigmoidoscopy, or colonoscopy. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and/or targeted therapy, depending on the stage and location of the cancer.

Brachydactyly syndactyly syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the hands and feet. It is characterized by the absence or underdevelopment of certain fingers or toes, and can also include webbing between them. This condition is typically inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a chance that their child will inherit it. The genetic basis for brachydactyly syndactyly syndrome has been linked to mutations in the HOXD13 gene on chromosome 2q31.

Brachyolmia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is characterized by the presence of generalized platyspondyly without significant long bone abnormalities and short stature. Brachyrachia is an exact synonym for brachyolmia.

Branchiooculofacial syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects an individual's development, particularly during embryonic and fetal stages. This condition is characterized by abnormalities in the branchial arches, which are structures in the neck that develop into various organs such as the ear, throat, and tongue.

Symptoms of Branchiooculofacial syndrome can include cleft palate, hearing problems, abnormalities of the facial bones, and underdevelopment of the thyroid gland. In some cases, affected individuals may also experience growth retardation and low birth weight.

The disorder is usually inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the gene responsible for the condition is sufficient to cause the disease. However, the exact genetic basis of Branchiooculofacial syndrome remains unclear, and researchers continue to study this complex disorder in order to better understand its causes and potential treatments.

Brody myopathy is a type of neuromuscular disease that affects the skeletal muscles. It is characterized by difficulty relaxing muscles and muscle stiffness following exercise or other strenuous activity.

Brooke Spiegler Syndrome is a skin disease characterized by the development of multiple types of tumors from the skin. It has a genetic basis, specifically involving a heterozygous mutation in the CYLD gene on chromosome 16q12. The syndrome has been defined as having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.
It is also known by the acronyms BSS and SBS, and it is sometimes referred to as Spiegler-Brooke Syndrome or CYLD cutaneous syndrome.

Brown-Vialetto-van Laere syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by sensorineural hearing loss and various cranial nerve palsies, most commonly affecting the motor components of the 7th and 9th to 12th cranial nerves. It is caused by mutations in the MYBHAI gene, which encodes a transcription factor involved in the development and maintenance of hair cells in the inner ear. Symptoms usually appear during infancy or early childhood and can include hearing loss, balance problems, facial weakness, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment may involve cochlear implants and speech therapy to help improve communication and language skills.

malignant pleural solitary fibrous tumor is a type of cancer that arises from the fibrous tissues surrounding the lungs. It is also known as malignant mesothelioma, which is a rare and aggressive form of cancer that affects the lining of the lungs and chest wall. Symptoms include chest pain, shortness of breath, coughing up blood, and swelling in the chest or abdomen. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

Fetal alcohol spectrum disorder is a type of developmental and physical disorder that occurs due to maternal alcohol consumption during pregnancy. It is characterized by birth defects, behavioral issues, and learning difficulties in children.

Chorioamnionitis is a medical condition in which the fetal membranes (amnion and chorion) become inflamed due to a bacterial infection. It is also known as intra-amniotic infection or pyelonephritis of the newborn. The condition can lead to complications for both the mother and the baby, including preterm labor, premature birth, and fetal distress. It is typically diagnosed through a combination of physical examination, ultrasound, and blood tests. Treatment may involve antibiotics and hospitalization to ensure the safety of both the mother and the baby.

Funisitis is not a common term in medical science. It is possible that you may be referring to another connective tissue disease, such as eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA), which is also sometimes referred to as Churg-Strauss syndrome. EGPA is a rare autoimmune disorder characterized by inflammation of the blood vessels and tissues in the body, particularly those associated with the respiratory system. The exact cause of EGPA is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be triggered by an autoimmune response, where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy cells and tissues in the body. Symptoms of EGPA can include respiratory problems such as coughing, wheezing, or difficulty breathing; skin rashes; joint pain; and swelling in the legs, ankles, feet, or hands. If you have any concerns about your health, it is important to speak with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Dent disease is a type of X-linked recessive disease that affects the renal tubules in the kidneys, leading to a buildup of calcium and other substances in the urine. It can also cause nephrolithiasis (kidney stones) and chronic kidney failure. The condition is caused by mutations in either the CLCN5 or OCRL1 gene, which are located on the X chromosome. It has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as tubular proteinuria, hypercalciuria, calcium nephrolithiasis, nephrocalcinosis, and chronic kidney failure.

Cardiomyopathy is a type of heart disease characterized by the deterioration of the heart muscle, which can lead to a weakened and enlarged heart. There are several types of cardiomyopathy, including dilated cardiomyopathy and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. It can be caused by a variety of factors such as genetics, medications, infections, and metabolic disorders. Cardiomyopathy can lead to heart failure and other complications if left untreated. Treatment options may include lifestyle changes, medications, and surgery.

Epilepsy is a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent seizures. An electroclinical syndrome, on the other hand, refers to a specific type of epilepsy that is defined by a cluster of clinical entities displaying a particular set of electro-clinical characteristics. These characteristics may include age at onset, cognitive and developmental antecedents and consequences, motor and sensory examinations, EEG features, provoking or triggering factors, and patterns of seizure occurrence with respect to sleep. So while epilepsy is a broader term encompassing many different types of seizures, an electroclinical syndrome is a more specific subtype of epilepsy that is characterized by these particular sets of clinical characteristics.

Neonatal period electroclinical syndrome is a type of electroclinical syndrome that affects newborn infants during the neonatal period, which typically lasts from birth to 4 weeks of age. The term "electroclinical syndrome" refers to a combination of clinical and electrical abnormalities in the brain or nervous system.

Neonatal period electroclinical syndrome can be caused by various factors such as infections, genetic disorders, trauma, or other medical conditions that affect fetal development. Symptoms may include seizures, fever, poor feeding, and irritability. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of neurological exams, electroencephalography (EEG), and other diagnostic tests such as blood tests or imaging studies.

Treatment for neonatal period electroclinical syndrome depends on the underlying cause and may involve medications to control seizures, antibiotics to treat infections, or other therapies to manage symptoms. In some cases, infants with this condition may require intensive care and monitoring in a hospital setting.

It is important for parents and caregivers of newborns to be aware of the signs and symptoms of neonatal period electroclinical syndrome and to seek immediate medical attention if they suspect their child may have this condition. Early diagnosis and treatment can improve outcomes for infants with this type of electroclinical syndrome.

Infancy electroclinical syndrome, also known as infantile seizure disorder, is a type of electroclinical syndrome. It refers to a group of epileptic conditions that typically begin during infancy and are characterized by abnormal electrical activity in the brain. Infancy electroclinical syndrome can occur between birth and one year of age, making it a subset of early-onset epilepsy.

Childhood-onset epilepsy is a broad term that encompasses various types of epilepsy syndromes that have their onset during childhood. One such type is the electroclinical syndrome known as childhood electroclinical syndrome, which is characterized by recurrent seizures that start during childhood, typically between one and 12 years of age. The exact cause of this condition is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to abnormal brain development or function. Treatment options for childhood electroclinical syndrome may include medications, dietary changes, and other therapies aimed at managing seizures and improving quality of life.

Adolescence-adult electroclinical syndrome (AAECS) is a type of absence epilepsy that begins during adolescence or young adulthood. It is characterized by recurrent seizures with loss of awareness, which can include symptoms such as staring into space, unresponsiveness, and convulsions. The onset of AAECS typically occurs between the ages of 10 and 35 years old. It is important to note that absence epilepsy is a type of epilepsy that is characterized by brief periods of unconsciousness without any motor activity.
Variable age at onset electroclinical syndrome is a type of electroclinical syndrome that is characterized by the development of seizures later in life with a variable age of onset and duration.
Early onset absence epilepsy is a type of childhood electroclinical syndrome, characterized by the occurrence of typical absence seizures starting between the age of four and ten years.

Early infantile epileptic encephalopathy (EIEE) is a type of neonatal period electroclinical syndrome that is characterized by tonic spasms and partial seizures. It is also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy with Burst-Suppression.

This is a description of 3 Methylcrotonyl coa carboxylase deficiency. It is an autosomal recessive disorder that affects muscle tissue and is characterized by low levels of the enzyme 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase, which helps break down proteins containing the amino acid leucine. Symptoms include muscular hypotonia, muscular atrophy, feeding difficulties, recurrent episodes of vomiting and diarrhea, and lethargy. It is also known as 3-Methylcrotonylglycinuria, 3MCC deficiency, and BMCC deficiency.

Aceruloplasminemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by progressive neurodegeneration of the retina and basal ganglia, and diabetes mellitus. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the ceruloplasmin gene.

Agat deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids, specifically creatine. It results from a mutation in the GATM gene which leads to a deficiency of arginine:glycine amidinotransferase, an enzyme essential for the synthesis of creatine. This deficiency can result in neurological symptoms such as seizures and developmental delays. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Cox deficiency infantile mitochondrial myopathy is a rare genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness, lactic acidosis, and abnormal heart and kidney function. It is caused by a deficiency of the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase, which is responsible for producing energy in cells. The condition is usually fatal in infancy, and there is no specific treatment available. However, supportive care can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life for affected individuals.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type cblc is a rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the MMALAC gene. It is one of several types of methylmalonic acidemia, which are characterized by the accumulation of methylmalonyl-CoA, a metabolite that is important for the synthesis of certain amino acids.

People with cblc have difficulty producing enough AdoCbl and MeCbl, two essential coenzymes required for the proper functioning of enzymes involved in metabolism. As a result, they may experience symptoms such as vomiting, lethargy, seizures, and developmental delays.

Diagnosis typically involves measuring levels of methylmalonic acid and other metabolites in the blood, as well as genetic testing to identify mutations in the MMALAC gene. Treatment may involve dietary restrictions and supplements to provide necessary nutrients, such as B12, or enzyme replacement therapy to replace the missing coenzymes.

It is important for individuals with cblc to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their symptoms and ensure their overall well-being.

Methylmalonic aciduria and homocystinuria type CblD is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of proteins in the body. It is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (MCM), which is responsible for converting methylmalonyl-CoA, a harmful compound, into harmless components. This results in an accumulation of methylmalonic acid and homocysteine in the blood, leading to symptoms such as vomiting, lethargy, seizures, and developmental delays in infants. Vitamin metabolic disorders are a group of inherited conditions caused by the body's inability to properly process vitamins and their co-factors. These disorders can cause a wide range of symptoms, including fatigue, weakness, and poor growth. They can also cause more severe complications, such as brain damage or death.
There are many different types of vitamin metabolic disorders, each caused by a specific deficiency in one or more vitamins or their co-factors. Some common examples include cystic fibrosis, which is caused by a deficiency in the protein that helps transport fats; and phenylketonuria, which is caused by a deficiency in an amino acid that is necessary for the synthesis of proteins.
Diagnosis of vitamin metabolic disorders often requires specialized testing, as the symptoms can be similar to those of other conditions. Treatment typically involves supplements and dietary changes to ensure adequate intake of the deficient vitamins or co-factors. In some cases, enzyme replacement therapy may also be necessary. With proper treatment, many people with vitamin metabolic disorders can lead healthy lives.

ornithine translocase deficiency (OTD) is a genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids in the body. Tyrosinemia type I is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of tyrosine, an amino acid. Treatment usually involves a special diet that restricts the intake of tyrosine and other related compounds, as well as medications to manage symptoms.

Tyrosinemia type III, also known as neonatal hepatopathy with conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the deficiency of 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase (HPPD), an enzyme responsible for breaking down tyrosine.
